<HEAD>Music Festival or Spectacle: The 20-Year Difference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEWISVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty years after a pop festival took over this <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> suburb, a beer company is sponsoring a rock fest that shows the <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION> era is long past. Organizers put together the 1969 <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lewisville </LOCATION> in seven weeks with a shoestring budget, but <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has pushed this weekend's concert series for more than a year with television ads and other promotions. At the shows, the psychedelic drugs of yesteryear will give way to drinking arrangements for designated drivers. `` The whole tone of the two shows 20 years apart is remarkably different,'' <PERSON> Angus </PERSON> <PERSON> Wynne </PERSON>, who promoted the <LOCATION> Lewisville </LOCATION> festival, said Tuesday. Just three weeks after the <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION> rock festival in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> state </LOCATION>, about 120,000 people spent three days on a field outside <LOCATION> Lewisville </LOCATION> to hear the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> <PERSON> Joplin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Santana </PERSON>, Sly and the Family Stone, B.B. King, Grand Funk Railway, Led Zeppelin and others. This weekend, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> hopes to draw 500,000 people to concerts in six <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> cities, including performances by the Who in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. The concerts culminate a 16-month campaign by the company. In addition to the Who, performances by <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kool </PERSON> and the Gang, <PERSON> Natalie </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> and many others are planned in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Midland-Odessa </LOCATION>. It took <PERSON> Wynne </PERSON> seven weeks and $ 120,000 to line up all 30 acts. Promoters of the <LOCATION> Lewisville </LOCATION> festival said they lost $ 100,000. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> has n't disclosed its budget, but the Who grossed $ 1.04 million at a concert before 47,000 fans in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> three weeks ago. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> has pledged to give at least $ 1 million in proceeds to the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Special Olympics. The company and promoters have made elaborate security arrangements. People will need wristbands to gain access to the concerts. Designated drivers will receive different colored bands entitling them to free soft drinks and baring them from buying beer. Twenty years ago, drugs were common, but the crowd behaved. There were only 36 arrests, most for public intoxication. `` Psychedelics and pot, I believe, were the prevalent stimulants of choice,'' said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Houston </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Denton </LOCATION> judge who was mayor of <LOCATION> Lewisville </LOCATION> from 1969 to 1973. When it was over, residents were surprised by the long-haired, easygoing rock fans. Some concertgoers mowed lawns and babysat for residents during their stay. `` That was part of the mind-blow thing that went on here,'' <PERSON> Wynne </PERSON> said. `` People expected all these folks to be real nasty, and here they were handing them flowers, just as polite as they could be. It disarmed them totally.''
