<HEAD>Study Shows Fish Defects Down but Pollution Still a Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A recent study of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> found fewer fish with bent fins, dwarfism or liver abnormalities associated with pollution, but researchers say the inlet is far from environmentally sound. `` We do n't conclude from the study that in fact things are getting better,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, senior scientist at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aquarium </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Edgerton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>. Nearly 200 winter flounder caught one day in mid-May showed fewer instances of cancerous lesions as well as other defects, compared to studies in the early 1980s. However, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said Wednesday, defects were markedly higher than the numbers found in cleaner environments further out in the sea. `` No changes have gone on in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> yet,'' he said, adding that partially treated sewage still is being dumped there. The state plans to spend $ 6.1 billion to clean up the pollution, which then-candidate <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> frequently cited in running against Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in last year's presidential campaign.
