<FIRST>r i PM-PalestinianEconomy     08-31 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palestinian Economy,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economic Pressure Mounts on Palestinians in West Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In days past, weddings in <PERSON> Hamad </PERSON> <PERSON> Badr </PERSON>'s family called for the slaughter of 20 sheep. But when a brother got married three months ago, two were sacrifice enough. The wedding was a victim of the 20-month intefadeh, or uprising against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation, which has squeezed livelihoods and altered lives for Palestinians throughout the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Repeated strikes by Palestinian workers, curfews imposed by the Israeli army and a drop in tourism have slashed incomes. As the economy has declined, the Jordanian dinar _ the key currency in the occupied lands _ has plunged in value by 50 percent, further ravaging savings and paychecks. Badr, whose family has owned a four-table restaurant in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s walled <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> for 25 years, said his business has been devastated. `` Before, if you wanted to get food, you'd have to wait outside for half an hour,'' said <PERSON> Badr </PERSON>, who now closes for the day at noon to comply with the orders of clandestine uprising leaders. `` Today you see: in a half an hour, we sold only two Coca-Colas.'' Nearly all Palestinians insist that the struggle for daily bread has not weakened their will to resist Israeli occupation. But the dinar's recent plunge coincided with a seeming drop of intensity in the uprising and an increase in factional squabbling in <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> ranks. `` If you are angry and hungry, you have to satisfy your hunger first,'' explained <PERSON> Tarik </PERSON> <PERSON> Said </PERSON>, who owns a photo shop near <LOCATION> Badr </LOCATION>'s restaurant But he said that rather than forcing an end to resistance, more violence is the likely result. An official of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s military government in the occupied lands said economic hardship was beginning to be felt in a widespread way for the first time but that it was too early to say it would mean an end to the uprising. <PERSON> Samir </PERSON> <PERSON> Saleh </PERSON>, an economist at the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said Palestinian incomes have fallen and buying power is probably half what it was when the uprising began in December 1987. Average incomes per capita declined by 25 percent from a pre-uprising level of $ 1,000 a month. <PERSON> Saleh </PERSON> said the falling value of the dinar `` has disastrous effects.'' The currency has been a major means of payment and savings for Palestinians since <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> lost the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in 1967. `` Here people only believed in God and the dinar,'' said <PERSON> Nabil </PERSON> <PERSON> Feidy </PERSON>, a money changer on <PERSON> Salah </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Din </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> in east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. The dinar was worth $ 3 early last year, but fell to less than $ 1 in July before recovering recently to about $ 1.50. Hospital workers, college teachers, Islamic preachers and tens of thousands of private employees still earn wages in dinars, and most paychecks have not risen as the dinar's purchasing power declined. <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, an Islamic preacher who dropped by to visit <PERSON> Badr </PERSON>, said he was forced to move his wife and two children out of their apartment and into a single room of his father's house. `` My salary is 160 dinars,'' said <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, noting that it used to be worth about $ 480 but now is worth $ 200. `` The impact on people here is devastating,'' said <PERSON> Feidy </PERSON>, the money changer. `` The worst part is that people have their dinars in Jordanian banks and they ca n't bring them.'' In an effort to stem the flow of orders and money from the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> sharply curtailed travel and financial transfers across the <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Palestinians can now bring in only 200 dinars a person per month. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has countered a tax boycott by Palestinians with increased fees on vehicles. <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Jafaar </PERSON>, a teacher who has seen his salary cut in half because of the frequent strikes and school closures, said fees on his car have risen to the equivalent of about $ 700 a year from $ 80. He has opened a small grocery store in his home. `` The shop is not a way of living but it helps.'' he said.
</TEXT>
