<FIRST>r w PM-Smells     08-31 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smells,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Removal of Bad Odors Seen as Prime Need in Third World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> wants to improve Third World cities _ by making them smell better. Not only are odors from bad sanitation and bad fuel for cooking and heating offensive to the nose, they're unhealthy, says <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION>, a senior urban planner for the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. People in <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s biggest city, burn a lot of dung and wood. In <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, it's wood and charcoal. That pollutes indoor air in a way that may be related to a range of lung diseases, tuberculosis and cancer, <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> says. The pollution comes from poor ventilation, regardless of the kind of fuel. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>'s study, `` Environmental Dilemmas and the Urban Poor,'' was made public Wednesday as part of a more general report called `` Environment and the Poor: Development Strategies for a Common Agenda.'' Women and children, who spend more time at home, are probably affected more than men, he said. `` The adverse effects of household airborne and water-carried wastes on child mortality and female life expectancy are of no less global proportions than, say, the destruction of tropical forests, and in immediate human terms may be the most urgent of all worldwide environmental problems,'' <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> wrote. The bank is the biggest source of aid loans to Third World countries, lending more than $ 19 billion a year. `` Dealing with bad smells _ human waste and indoor air pollution _ will get you a bigger immediate return in human well-being than many other things we do,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sewell </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Overseas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which published the report. The council is a private research group, financed by foundations. <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION> reported that new kinds of cooking stoves designed for Third World use have run into trouble because they are n't what people are accustomed to. But he added that they are a good idea because a 10 percent improvement of cooking efficiency could save millions of tons of wood a year and help solve the health problem. `` Contain the heat, vent the exhausts,'' he advised. Ventilated pit latrines cut down costs by two-thirds and standard specifications can be reduced to make them cheaper and to use more local labor, he said. He called for more research not only on stoves, but also on toilets that flush when water is poured into them and small, maneuverable pumps for latrine systems. Such things may seem second class, but the people who use them and the donors who provide them will learn to appreciate them, he said. `` Short-term gains in health may come to be valued by the poor as much as or more than the loss of status they perceive for having a second-class _ that is, less than standard _ system for cooking and waste disposal,'' he wrote.
