<FIRST>r w PM-MethanolDispute     08-31 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Methanol Dispute,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Companies Step up Campaign Against President's Methanol Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The oil industry is intensifying its attack on a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration plan requiring the use of methanol in some cars by 1995 to control the growing smog problem in the nation's most polluted cities The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, which represents the major oil companies, has hired consultant <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> to speak against replacing gasoline-burning engines with those capable of running on methanol, or wood alcohol. <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>, a mechanical engineer and former <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> official, told reporters Wednesday that his research showed methanol is no less environmentally harmful than gasoline. He also contends it is more costly and less safe. `` Methanol is not an inherently clean fuel,'' he said. `` It is just as dirty as gasoline.'' The oil industry has voiced strong doubts about methanol since <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed in June that 500,000 cars capable of burning methanol be sold by 1995 in cities with the most serious air pollution problems, and that 1 million be sold each year starting in 1997. The administration contends that methanol-burning cars will help reduce the formation of smog because they emit fewer hydrocarbons. It also says increased use of methanol will reduce the nation's growing reliance on foreign oil used to make gasoline The oil industry, which produces about 100 billion gallons of gasoline a year, has a powerful interest in keeping it the predominant transportation fuel. <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> acknowledged that tests show cars running on methanol emit fewer poisonous hydrocarbons than those burning gasoline. But he said the administration has overlooked or discounted research that indicates methanol-burning engines emit far more formaldehyde, a chemical that helps form smog. The major oil companies say they have been researching possible uses of methanol as a transportation fuel for years and will continue to do so. But, through their trade association, they have strongly criticized the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposal as too ambitious. They say more emphasis should be put on researching cleaner formulations of gasoline.
</TEXT>
