<FIRST>r p PM-Abortion-Election     08-31 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Election,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida House Race Shows Pro-Life Movement Thriving, Group Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-abortion activists say the outcome of a special <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> congressional election is a `` pivotal victory'' in the wake of last month's <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling on abortion. A leader of the abortion rights movement, however, said Wednesday that ethnic issues, not abortion, fueled state Sen. <PERSON> Ileana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>'s victory over Democrat <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>, a Republican and the first Cuban-American elected to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, defeated <PERSON> Richman </PERSON> on Tuesday for the seat left vacant by the death of veteran Democratic Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>. `` Ileana could not have won the vote with just the Hispanic vote,'' <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Faucher </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters. `` There is not a majority of Hispanics in the district. `` There had to be other issues involved, and we feel that definitely the abortion issue played a major factor in the race,'' she said. `` <PERSON> Ileana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>'s win is a pivotal victory for the pro-life movement.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s 5-4 ruling July 3, which gave states greater power to limit abortions, appeared on the court's docket as <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> vs. Reproductive Health Services. <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> Michelman </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abortion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, said abortion `` was not the issue'' in the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> race. `` Nothing was an issue there that could supersede the ethnicity issue,'' Ms. <PERSON> Michelman </PERSON> said. `` The fact is that no issue, even the issue of choice, could overwhelm the ethnicity issue.'' The district is about 40 percent Hispanic and unofficial returns showed that predominantly Latin precincts had turnouts of more than 60 percent and gave Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> majorities of 80 percent to 90 percent. She carried the entire district by a 53 percent to 47 percent margin. During the campaign, Ms. <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>, 37, said she favored more restrictions on abortion. <PERSON> Richman </PERSON> said he favored more choice. However, with polls indicating most voters supported abortion rights, the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidate said abortion was more of a state legislative issue than a congressional issue. Abortion rights leaders have contended that state legislative victories in races in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> indicated movement in their direction in the wake of the court ruling. Ms. <PERSON> Faucher </PERSON>, however, said anti-abortion candidates have won in races in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and two <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> legislative districts. Ms. <PERSON> Michelman </PERSON> denied that abortion was an important issue in those races.
