<FIRST>r a PM-Transplants-Ethics     08-31 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transplants-Ethics,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethical Rules Say Parent Can Donate Liver to Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Living donors can ethically give up part of their livers for transplants, but such donations generally should be limited to parents supplying organs for their children, according to guidelines released today. The proposed rules were developed at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>, where doctors hope to perform the nation's first such transplant. Transplants involving whole or partial livers taken from the dead are now routine in many large medical centers. But because these organs are in short supply, doctors would like to begin transplanting parts of organs taken from the living. The body has two kidneys, and these are routinely donated to relatives with kidney failure. But because the body has only one liver, this organ can not be entirely removed for transplantation. The new surgery would remove one lobe of a healthy person's liver and transplant it into an infant with kidney failure. The donor's missing section of liver eventually grows back, and in the baby, the piece of organ grows along with the child `` We believe that from the perspectives of both recipient and donor, the benefits outweigh the risks and that it is ethically appropriate to proceed with a trial of liver transplantation using a parent as a living donor,'' wrote Dr. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> A. Singer and colleagues. The doctors published the guidelines, which resulted from a year-long series of seminars and discussions, in a report in the New England Journal of Medicine. A team led by Dr. <PERSON> Christoph </PERSON> <PERSON> Broelsch </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> surgeons hopes to perform the operation this fall. The operation has already been done in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. The doctors proposed that the donor should be the child's parent or, in rare cases, a mature sibling or grandparent. They said that when the donor is related to the recipient, the benefits of saving a life are most rewarding. Such transplants also have the best chance of succeeding. One of the child's parents will be asked to sign a consent form that states: `` The operation your child will have ... has never been performed.'' Doctors say that because of the shortage of organs from cadavers, up to half of all babies who need new livers die while awaiting transplants.
</TEXT>
