<SECOND>PM-Imported Pests, Bjt,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exotic Pests Threaten Farm Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL MONTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lured like other visitors to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> by the warm climate, record numbers of exotic insects are invading <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and posing an unprecedented threat to the state's $ 16 billion a year farm economy As of July, 1,185 potentially harmful pests have appeared in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, including fruit flies and gypsy moths, fire ants, Russian wheat aphids, Japanese beetles, mealy bugs and scales. `` We are being literally swamped,'' said <PERSON> Rosser </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON>, a county entomologist who supplied the statistics. `` The variety of insects is increasing, and the sheer number is increasing.'' Besides the climate, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> has become a magnet for imported insects because of the ease of international travel. More than 3.7 million foreigners passed through <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> last year, and at least some presumably slipped fresh fruit and vegetables past inspectors, officials said. One of the new pests, the ash whitefly, already has reached epidemic proportions in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and is racing for the state's agricultural heartland _ the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joaquin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The city, a hub for commerce with <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, boasts a burgeoning immigrant population with a taste for fruits and vegetables from their native countries. `` They have friends and family who are sending them a taste of home,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON>, a deputy county agricultural commissioner. <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said that although <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s farm production is negligible, the county acts as the entry for pests to the rest of the state _ the nation's leading agricultural producer. He noted that <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s belated response to a Mediterranean fruit fly infestation drew widespread publicity nine years ago, eventually costing the state $ 100 million to exterminate and farmers $ 100 million in losses. But similar invasions lately have become almost mundane. `` I hate to stress that, because I do n't want people to believe that the bug is any less dangerous,'' <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said. Nevertheless, three medfly infestations have occurred in the county within the last 12 months, each costing roughly $ 1 million to eradicate and each drawing comparatively scant public attention. The county's budget for plant quarantine last year was more than $ 784,000, an almost 54 percent increase over fiscal year 1977-78, officials said. Treatment methods vary for different types of fruit flies, but early detection is a fundamental strategy, made possible by checking more than 160,000 baited traps set throughout the state. `` It's almost like battling forest fires,'' <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON> said. `` It's a lot easier to put it out as soon as it gets started. Discoveries of less notorious pests are charted each month by <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON>, whose microscopic scrutiny detected five new types of insects in the county last year and three so far this year. Although agriculture officials have established methods of dealing with fruit fly infestations, other kinds of insects can be neither readily identified nor exterminated. One of the most ruinous new pests, the ash whitefly, apparently hitchhiked to the suburban <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fernando </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. It has no natural enemies in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and its numbers are exploding. `` It is totally out of control,'' <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said. `` The only thing limiting the population is the number of trees they have to eat. It is expanding as fast as it can, and chemical -LRB- pesticide -RRB- control is just totally not feasible.'' Although fruit flies, which lay their eggs in hundreds of fruits and vegetables, are like a cancer, <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said the ash whitefly acts more like a low-grade virus. It attaches itself to the underside of leaves and slowly sucks the life out of trees. At first, agriculture officials were unconcerned because they believed the tiny new invader only attacked ornamental trees like the ash, <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said. But they later discovered the ash whitefly thrives in dozens of varieties of trees, including olive, pear, apple and peach trees. To combat the ash whitefly, agriculture officials have dispatched an entomologist to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> to collect several varieties of <LOCATION> Encarsia </LOCATION>, pinhead-sized wasps that are the insect's natural enemy. If tests prove successful, millions of the tiny wasps could be released come winter, though it probably will be years before the wasps can significantly reduce the ash whitefly population.
