. </LOCATION> officials hinted to reporters this week that there is more evidence against him. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Takiff </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> demanded in a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> the right to cross-examine witnesses who appeared before the organization. The letter asked for the `` opportunity to prove ... that the indictments against Gen. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> are motivated politically representing nothing more than ` indictment diplomacy.''' <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, confirmed Wednesday that <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> would focus on narcotics, but she declined to offer any details. The term of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s provisional president, <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>, who was handpicked by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, expires today. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration and Panamanian opponents of the general are concerned <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> will name a puppet government and not hold free elections. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has tried unsuccessfully to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> from power for 18 months.
