<FIRST>r a PM-InsulinPump     08-31 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Insulin Pump,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Say New Insulin Pump Works</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A radio-controlled insulin pump implanted in diabetics' abdomens can free them from injections and may more closely mimic the way nature provides the essential hormone, according to a study published today. The pump can be programmed to vary the rate at which it releases insulin. Researchers hope this approach will help diabetics get better control of their blood sugar levels and avoid the disabling complications of their disease, such as blindness and kidney failure. `` It's a significant advance,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Saudek </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, where the pump was developed. `` This is, in my view, the first successful long-term experience with variable-rate implanted insulin pumps.'' Other implanted pumps tested in recent years have been hindered by problems, such as clogged lines. The new pump was tested on 18 diabetics, and doctors said it generally worked well, although four pumps became blocked when tissue grew over the catheter that releases the insulin. One malfunctioned because of a faulty microchip. Doctors can program the pumps to vary the rate at which they release insulin throughout the day. Patients use a hand-held radio transmitter to command the pumps to give out an extra burst of insulin after meals. While blood sugar control with the pumps was good, the doctors said that the best solution eventually may be a pump that senses the body's blood sugar levels and releases insulin as it's needed. An estimated 500,000 diabetic Americans require frequent insulin injections because their bodies fail to make enough of the hormone that breaks down sugar. The new pumps, manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> MiniMed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Sylmar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, were tested by <PERSON> Saudek </PERSON> and other doctors at <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>. They described the results in a report in the New England Journal of Medicine. Patients used the pump _ called a programmable implantable medication system, or PIMS _ for all their insulin needs for periods ranging from four months to two years. Except for two who withdrew from the experiment because of blocked catheters, the doctors said that patients `` have been uniformly happy with their pumps.'' The disk-shaped pumps, implanted in patients' abdomens, are 3 inches in diameter and weigh 7 ounces. They hold about 2 -LCB- teaspoons of insulin _ a two-month supply _ and can be refilled with a syringe. The devices have computer memories that will record an hourly history of all insulin released during three weeks. Researchers plan soon to test a slightly modified version of the pump on more patients. `` The expectation is that if these next trials go well, we would then apply to have the pump generally available to the diabetic population,'' <PERSON> Saudek </PERSON> said. The mechanism was based on the design of a device on the Viking space probe that delivered culture medium to Martian soil to see if anything would grow in it.
</TEXT>
