<SECOND>PM-Acid Rain-Costs,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acid Rain Legislation Would Mean Higher Electric Costs: Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The utility industry says consumers in many states should be prepared to pay as much as 10 percent more for electricity if legislation to curb acid rain becomes law. The industry contends such legislation will cost more than $ 5.5 billion a year. Environmentalists and analysts at the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the industry cost estimates provided Wednesday are too high, but concede the emission curbs required to reduce acid rain will be expensive. `` We're heartened that their numbers are coming out so close to ours,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kete </PERSON>, senior analyst in the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s office of air radiation, when asked about the utility industry figures. She said the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has estimated industry costs would be about $ 4 billion a year when full compliance with the proposed acid rain controls go into effect in 2000. The acid rain curbs are included in legislation before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> tightening federal air pollution laws. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration proposal calls for cutting annual sulfur dioxide emissions _ the chief source of acid rain _ by 10 million tons, mostly from coal-burning power plants. The report by the <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> projects industry costs as high as $ 120 billion over a 20-year period as a result of having to install pollution control equipment and make other adjustments to meet the emission curbs required by the legislation. Under some scenarios, costs could jump to as much as $ 7.1 billion a year after 2000, said the industry report, acknowledging that was a `` high-cost'' scenario that envisions failure of the administration's proposed emissions credit trading scheme and broad reliance by utilities on expensive `` scrubber'' technology instead of fuel switching. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Kete </PERSON> said the agency continues to believe that utilities will rely less than the industry believes on expensive technology, opt more for switching from high-sulfur to low-sulfur coal, and make the emissions credit system work. All of those factors would bring the industry estimates in line with the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> cost estimates, she said. According to the industry study, about 85 percent of the increased costs of complying with the proposed emission curbs would be borne by 15 states in the eastern half of the country where utilities rely heavily on high-sulfur coal to meet their generating needs. Utilities in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> together will face 44 percent of the annual costs nationwide, the industry group said. The other states in the group of 15 are <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. The additional costs will result in rate increases of more than 5 percent in 19 states with the sharpest increases _ 10.8 percent to 17.3 percent _ coming in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, according to the industry study. The others states facing rates increases of more than 5 percent were given as: <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, all 6 percent to 9 percent increase; and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, both 5.1 percent to 5.9 percent. Thirty-six of the 100 major utilities will have to impose rate increases of at least 10 percent, the industry group maintained. <PERSON> Kete </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has estimated average rate increases as a result of the additional pollution control requirements at about 2 percent with the highest increases in the 5 percent to 6 percent range. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON>, the industry group's senior vice president for energy and environment, said costs could be reduced by as much as 30 percent if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> eliminates provisions for emission caps for individual utilities and changes other restrictions he said are `` unnecessarily expensive.'' `` They're trying to trash the administration's acid rain proposal,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Dudek </PERSON>, an economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. He maintained the legislation already is flexible enough to allow utilities `` to pick sensible alternatives'' that meet the proposed emission standards and still hold down costs.
