 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has extended for two months its deadline for deciding whether to ban Red Dye No. 3 as a cancer-causing food additive. The agency, in announcing the extension Wednesday, said it has been evaluating research data submitted by the <ORGANIZATION> Certified </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Color </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> on the coloring that gives maraschino cherries their bright glow. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> had been prepared to act by the earlier deadline, which was Wednesday, when the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in July passed legislation calling for further study of the dye. The Senate has not yet acted on the legislation. Since 1960, when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> called for a ban on foods that cause cancer in laboratory animals, Red Dye No. 3 and other additives have been on a provisional list that allowed them to stay on the market for an additional two years pending further study. Since then, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has granted dozens of extensions of the provisional listing. The manufacturers association says the dye is not a primary cause of cancer and causes tumors only when used in doses higher than would ever be consumed through its use as a food coloring.
