<SECOND>PM-Salt,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Overweight Kids' Blood Pressures Sensitive to Salt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When overweight youngsters switch from high-salt to low-salt diets, their blood pressures fall dramatically, but the change in food has no effect on normal-size youngsters, a study published today shows. The work suggests that fat youngsters are more susceptible to the damaging effects of a high-salt diet. This helps explain why overweight people are especially prone to get high blood pressure. Doctors have long known that people who lose weight also lower their blood pressure. The latest work shows that mild sodium restriction also results in a significant drop in blood pressure, even when people remain overweight. `` In this study, we found that the blood pressure of obese adolescents is sensitive to dietary sodium intake, whereas the blood pressure of non-obese adolescents is not,'' the researchers wrote. They theorized that overweight people get high blood pressure because their bodies are less efficient at getting rid of salt. The study was directed by Dr. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocchini </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON> and published in the New England Journal of Medicine. The researchers studied 60 obese and 18 normal youngsters who ranged from age 10 to 16. They spent two weeks on a high-salt diet and two weeks on a low-salt diet. At the start of the study, the overweight youngsters' blood pressures were 19 points higher than the normal children's. After the low-salt regimen, the obese youngsters' fell 12 points, while the normal children's rose one. Thirty-six of the overweight children went on weight-loss diets and dropped an average of 17 pounds. At the lower weights, their blood pressures were no longer sensitive to salt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
