<HEAD>Americans in Colombia Edgy, but Not Panicked by Cartel Threats</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> are edgy about the drug traffickers' retaliatory campaign against the government but few say they sense any imminent personal danger. Nonetheless, some are packing their bags. `` I love <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, but I just ca n't live here right now,'' <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON>, who has lived in the country 18 years, said Wednesday in a telephone interview. She said other factors contributed to her decision to leave next week with her three daughters, but that the latest wave of violence `` just topped it off.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday recommended that Americans in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> leave the country to avoid being caught up in the violence. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> ordered the evacuation of all embassy dependents, apparently for fear of becoming the targets of the ruthless cocaine cartels. Traffickers are lashing out because of a government anti-narcotics offensive that has included a nationwide manhunt and the confiscation of more than $ 200 million in drug barons' property. Part of the campaign, sparked by the Aug. 18 assassination of popular presidential candidate Sen. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Galan </PERSON>, included renewal of an extradition treaty with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Traffickers are known to greatly fear extraditon to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON>, married to a Colombian, said she planned to spend a year in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with her daughters. Her husband, an economist with a private company in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, plans to stay behind for now but will look into job possibilities in the States, she said. She said she felt no direct threat, but admitted the tension of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> `` gets really tiring.'' A change of scene would also be welcome, she said. `` I'd like to see something different for a year,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON> said. `` Who knows? I may be back in a year. It may be too quiet for me over there.'' At <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, summer vacation ended Tuesday. On the first day of classes, all students were assembled and the headmaster told them to assure their parents special security measures were being taken. One teacher said the measures included constant contact between the school, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> mayor's office; strict measures to keep unauthorized people off campus and checks on any cars parked on the school's perimeter. The school has always employed guards and watchmen. `` The teachers are all there working with confidence and calm and without fear,'' she said, asking not to be identified by name. `` We do n't feel any particular threat to Americans.'' `` On the other hand, there are n't many of us left,'' she added. Of the school's 1,400 students, less than 10 percent are <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens, she noted. The American community shrank dramatically in late 1984, when extradition of drug traffickers to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> began. Angry cocaine cartel bosses threatened to kill five Americans for every dealer who was extradited to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> for trial. A bomb exploded outside the downtown <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, killing a female Colombian passer-by. Hundreds of Americans fled to the States, many of them executives in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies that before the drug violence had been frequent targets of the country's well-