 <PERSON> Georgio </PERSON> <PERSON> Sant </PERSON> ` <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON>, an avant-garde designer known for his elegant, clinging fashions, has He was 56. <PERSON> Sant </PERSON> ` <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> died of lung cancer Tuesday at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Luke </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> `` He was a highly original and imaginative designer,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Blass </PERSON>. `` He brought a lot of energy and ability to American fashions.'' <PERSON> Sant </PERSON> ` <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> became famous for his designs that used body-hugging stretch fabrics for comfortable, dressy clothing popular with <PERSON> Bianca </PERSON> <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>, <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunaway </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lena </PERSON> <PERSON> Horne </PERSON>, among Many of his ideas have since passed into the mainstream and can be seen in the collections of <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jean-Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaultier </PERSON> and <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Karan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sant </PERSON> ` <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> became a designer by In 1967, while working as a textile designer, the Italian-born count took some pieces of plastic home one evening and fashioned them into geometric shaped jewelry. The jewelry caught the eye of <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> <PERSON> Vreeland </PERSON>, then editor of <LOCATION> Vogue </LOCATION>, who published pictures of the work. <PERSON> Sant </PERSON> ` <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> won his first Coty Award for these designs the following He soon translated his ideas from plastic to tie-dyed fabrics, and entered the fashion business. He won his second Coty in 1970 for his clothes. <PERSON> Sant </PERSON> ` <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> once said, `` I like to do absolutely everything because one area always brings ideas for another Born Count <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> <PERSON> di </PERSON> <PERSON> Sant </PER