<HEAD>Japan's Doi Tells United States: No Nukes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leader of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest opposition party said in an interview published today that if she became prime minister she would ban <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear weapons from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Sydney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said such a policy might force the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> to abandon many of its operations in the <LOCATION> northwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, and it quoted <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Japanese officials as saying it could damage the alliance between the nations. <PERSON> Takako </PERSON> <PERSON> Doi </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, was quoted as telling the newspaper that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had pledged to consult with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> before carrying nuclear weapons into its territory, and that it was time to enforce the agreement. The popular Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> could become prime minister if the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> loses its control of parliament in an upcoming general election and the Socialists are able to forge a coalition with other opposition parties. `` Once the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> has promised, it must observe its promise,'' the Morning Herald quoted her as saying. `` It is a matter of principle. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> must face up to its responsibilities and hold diplomatic negotiations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> can not admit, from any country, ships carrying nuclear weapons.'' Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> said she was prepared to pursue the policy even if it denied the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> the ability to operate in the parts of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has ignored its pledge and routinely carries nuclear weapons into Japanese territory on ships. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> refuses to publicly confirm or deny whether its ships carry nuclear weapons. Such a policy has affected its relations with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, which has denied <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships suspected of carrying nuclear warheads entry to its ports. The <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> quoted a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat as saying a policy such as the one promoted by Ms. <PERSON> Doi </PERSON> would have a `` tremendous impact on our strategic posture'' and would be `` tantamount to an abrogation of the Japan-U.S. security treaty.'' It quoted a Japanese defense official as saying the change would `` produce a breakdown in the Japan-U.S. relationship and be a very serious source of instability in the region.'' Neither official was identified. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the only nation to have suffered atomic attacks, maintains a policy of not manufacturing, storing or allowing nuclear weapons to be introduced into the country.
