 The Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant was plagued by safety problems two months after federal agents raided it for evidence of alleged environmental crimes, according to an <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report. The safety inspection report for the week of Aug. 7-11, obtained Wednesday by The <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, said there was `` no improvement in the radiological protection areas'' at Rocky Flats during the past several months. A similar report, based on a plant inspection in July, detailed 10 serious problems with radiation protection at the plant. None of the specific problems cited in July resurfaced in August, however. Rocky Flats is operated by <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> under contract from the DOE. The plant produces plutonium triggers for nuclear bombs. A federal grand jury in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> is investigating officials from <LOCATION> Rockwell </LOCATION> and the DOE for allegedly conspiring to illegally dispose of radioactive and hazardous wastes. About 75 <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents and special officers from the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> raided the plant on June 6 after a search warrant was issued on an affidavit containing more than 100 pages of allegations. A <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the new safety inspections they started at Rocky Flats in early July are correcting many problems. But spokesman <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Heints </PERSON> admitted no factory is perfect, not even one that handles plutonium. `` We act on these things as soon as we are notified of them,'' he said. `` But with as many people as we have here, some people are just going to get careless.'' The plant employs about 6,000 people. The report, written by an unidentified <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> safety inspector, said an employee was seen in a radiation control area not wearing anti-contamination clothing. The employee then left the area without going through a required monitoring device. Another employee in a building where radioactive material is handled violated safety procedures by leaving doors open that should have been closed, the report said. `` These are just two of the numerous problems observed across the Rocky Flats site,'' the inspector wrote.
