<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia-Analysis 1stLd-Writethru   08-31 0949</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Analysis, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0489,0981</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombia's War With Traffickers: Little Chance of Quick Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts top three grafs for clarity. Pickup 4th pvs, `The official...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> is in a costly war with drug traffickers, and it appears to have little chance of a quick victory. The current campaign to crush drug lords and their private armies, if it continues, is likely to drag on for years before it succeeds, according to officials familiar with the situation. It will take billions of dollars and at least a decade to defeat the traffickers, a senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> said in response to a question during a briefing Wednesday. The official spoke on condition that his remarks be paraphrased, that he not be identified and that the briefing not be recorded. A former Colombian army intelligence officer told an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reporter that he, too, thinks it will take billions of dollars and well over a decade before drug traffickers are no longer a threat. The officer, a former major, said he has his doubts about whether the war can be won at all. He also spoke on condition of anonymity. The former army officer pointed out that there is no reason to believe government security forces will have any more success fighting drug traffickers than they have had combating leftist guerrillas. The army has been fighting leftist guerrillas for three decades, and the rebel forces have grown steadily to an estimated 10,000 combatants. The traffickers' power also has grown quickly. Fifteen years ago, some of today's millionaire and billionaire cocaine traffickers were pickpockets and pig farmers. Six years ago they offered to pay off <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s $ 10 billion foreign debt if the government would give them amnesty. The offer was rejected. Today, the traffickers have private armies totaling about 4,000 men, intelligence-gathering units, modern weapons and fleets of airplanes and helicopters, the former major said. To meet this growing threat, the government has sharply increased its spending on security forces, and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has authorized $ 65 million of emergency assistance to <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> to fight the traffickers. Unfortunately, it all may be too little, too late. `` A lot of army officers know it would take billions of dollars to exterminate all of the drug traffickers, to destroy their empires,'' the former intelligence officer said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been giving <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> about $ 10 million a year to fight the traffickers, an amount that seems small considering the urgency the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has given the drug problem and the traffickers' power. In the last five years, an AP reporter in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> has seen many signs of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s inability to combat the cocaine problem. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> DEA agent once said that <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s anti-drug agents were so poorly equipped that they had to beg gas from their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> counterparts to go on drug raids. An <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> pilot flying search-and-destroy missions over the eastern jungles to eradicate coca plantations told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> reporter that pilots need longer range planes to be effective. And farmers in the Andes in southeast <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> told the reporter they were n't worried about police helicopters swooping down periodically to destroy coca bushes. New bushes are planted immediately after police leave, they said. Army troops in the field are poorly equipped. Boots are worn until they almost fall apart. As AP reporter in combat areas has seen soldiers flagging down banana trucks and forcing drivers to transport troops because the army does not have enough trucks of its own. Meanwhile, the traffickers use the most modern automatic weapons, including light antitank weapons. The former intelligence officer told The <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> that former colleagues told him recently about raids on one trafficker's hideout that turned up records indicating he spent $ 100,000 a month gathering information. Former President <PERSON> Belisario </PERSON> <PERSON> Betancur </PERSON>, speaking of the traffickers during his 1982-86 term, said: `` <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> is fighting against something that is stronger than the state.'' <PERSON> Betancur </PERSON>'s justice minister, <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lara </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON>, was murdered, riddled with bullets because raids on cocaine laboratories had hurt the traffickers too much. In the last 10 years, traffickers have killed 220 judges and other court employes, two newspaper editors, a justice minister, an attorney general, hundreds of policemen and soldiers and dozens of others perceived by traffickers as a threat to their business. To counter the violence, the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> government has started for the first time in 30 years spending more on the military than on education. The government increased the military's share of the 1990 budget to 17 percent from 10 percent, for a total of $ 560 million. That is almost certainly bound to limit growth of spending on schools, hospitals and other public works. It is that sort of thinking that got <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s guerrillas started three decades ago. Progressive governments have done much to develop the country, but extreme poverty is still a problem. Many children grow up never tasting meat or milk. Cardboard boxes discarded in front of houses disappear in minutes, taken by people who sell them. People digging in garbage dumps for bones to sell to chemical companies and for such things as bottles are so common that there are labor unions among the scavengers. Such shortcomings are eventually going to have to be weighed as <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s guerrillas continue to press for changes in government spending to help the country's poor people. A costly and continued war against drug traffickers will make that difficult if not impossible unless there is massive aid from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and elsewhere.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE: <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Wells </PERSON>, The Associated Press bureau chief of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, has been based in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> since 1978.
