 The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> team that will monitor elections in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in February will be led by <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney general with a long record of government service. After the announcement was made Wednesday, <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, 69, declined to say whether he thought <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> would hold a free and fair election. He said he would bring to the job a long experience in hard-fought campaigns. `` I've been a candidate; I've been involved in elections, I once even ran a recount in a gubernatorial election in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> many years ago,'' he said in a telephone interview. A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official, who demanded anonymity, said <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> government opposed <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>'s appointment and resisted it for weeks. No one at <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> would comment on the appointment. The elections come at a crucial point in <LOCATION> Nicargua </LOCATION>'s history. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> recently withdrew its military support for the Contra rebels, and the fighting force is expected to disband. <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> is best known for resigning as attorney general in protest during the `` Saturday night massacre'' episode in the Watergate scandal. He quit the night of Oct. 10, 1973, the same night President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> fired Watergate special prosecutor <PERSON> Archibald </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>. <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> and a group of jurists and former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials called the Commission on the Independence of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCAT