<HEAD>Congresswoman Says New Equipment Might Not Have Detected Bomb</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with congresswoman questioning FAA order; picks
up 4th graf pvs, The airlines.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The explosives detection devices the government wants installed at 40 of the world's busiest airports might not have detected the bomb that destroyed <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 last year, a congresswoman said today. Rep. <PERSON> Cardiss </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, D-Ill., chairwoman of the House Government Operations transportation subcommittee, said more work on the detection equipment is needed She questioned whether it would have picked up the relatively small bomb _ believed to have weighed about one pound _ that brought down Flight 103 last December over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, killing 270 people. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s detection standards were set several years ago and have not been revised as its knowledge about explosives and terrorists has become more precise,'' the congresswoman wrote the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> recently in comments made available today. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> regulation issued Wednesday was made possible because of evolving technology that allows detection of chemicals in plastic explosives. The equipment likely to be installed detects nitrogen, a component in most explosives but also present in small amounts in wool, leather and nylon. This makes detection of small bombs difficult, Ms. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said, because the device does not determine the source of the nitrogen. `` The smaller the amount of explosive, the more difficult it is to detect in the background nitrogen content of the suitcase,'' she wrote. The airlines, which would have to pay an estimated $ 393 million over the next 10 years to install detection devices, have questioned the cost and effectiveness of the technology available to meet the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> requirement. `` We can not support the widespread deployment of this equipment in the near term because its capability has not yet been demonstrated,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, an airline industry group. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, which can require airlines to follow certain procedures abroad as a condition for flying into <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airports, says it will continue to consider whether to require the new screening on all international flights by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers _ a move that could send the cost to airlines to an estimated $ 896 million by 1999. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has acquired six prototype screening devices, the first already installed at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. The others are scheduled for installation by the end of the year at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Gatwick </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and airports in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> declined to identify the other 34 airports, citing security considerations and the possibility there could be some shifts in those affected. Investigators have concluded that the bomb that exploded over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> was hidden in checked luggage loaded in the forward cargo compartment of the New York-bound <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747. The rule does not require a particular device but says one called Thermal Neutron Analysis has been `` shown to have the highest degree of explosives detection currently possible for detecting known civilian and military explosives, manufactured here and abroad.'' Any system used by the airlines must be approved by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>. The rule requires that the system be automated, detect specified quantities and configurations of explosives as defined by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and be safe for operators and baggage. The <ORGANIZATION> TNA </ORGANIZATION> units are estimated to cost $ 750,000 each, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said. It said this cost is expected to drop as production increases. The device was developed by <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Applications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> under an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> contract. The agency said it has been tested successfully at several airports. The system emits low-energy neutrons that pass through luggage and interact with the chemical elements in explosives, triggering an alarm. The detection is done by computer.
