<HEAD>Nevada Gaming, Business Pioneer Morris `Moe' Dalitz Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> `` Moe'' <PERSON> Dalitz </PERSON>, a gaming pioneer who helped develop several major <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> casinos but was later dogged by his early ties to organized crime, died early today. He was 89 and had been ill for some time. <PERSON> Dalitz </PERSON> was born near <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and he and his brothers operated a chain of cleaners in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. Shortly after coming to <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> in 1949, he acquired an ownership interest in the Desert Inn and Stardust hotels. In the early 1950s he joined partners to form <ORGANIZATION> Paradise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which built the city's convention center, a major hospital and shopping center and several buildings at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevada-Las </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vegas </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dalitz </PERSON> recently was involved in the development of the Fitzgerald hotel-casino, but he never applied for a gaming license there because of concerns over past crime ties. He was listed in a 1978 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> attorney general's report on organized crime, but was never accused of a crime. In later years <PERSON> Dalitz </PERSON> was known as a philanthropist and received the 1976 Humanitarian Award from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and Hospital. Funeral services were pending.
</TEXT>
