<HEAD>Bridge Collapses on Baltimore-Washington Parkway; 14 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with no one else believed trapped, quote
from governor, other detail, and to CORRECT time of accident to 6:30 a.m.
sted 7, reflecting official change. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos ANCX1,2, WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATTY REINERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAUREL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bridge being built over a major roadway collapsed during rush hour this morning, raining debris on commuters and injuring 14 people, state police said. One woman was in critical condition after the collapse of the Route 198 overpass over the <LOCATION> Baltimore-Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parkway </LOCATION>, which came about 6:30 a.m. while workers were pouring concrete, police said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Park Police Deputy Chief <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kusick </PERSON> said four of the injured were in a car that was crushed under the overpass. Another was in a second car that was hit by debris, while the other nine were construction workers. Rescue and construction workers drilled holes into the pile of rubble and carried away debris a piece at a time searching for other vehicles that may have been trapped. By midday, however, officials concluded no one else was in the rubble, and heavy equipment was brought in to clean it up. The critically injured woman was taken by helicopter to the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trauma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, said state police spokesman Sgt. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ireton </PERSON>. The others were taken to various hospitals, he said. State police spokesman <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said the collapse caused tremendous traffic backups. The southbound parkway was closed at Route 32, and traffic was being detoured around the area. <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> police, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Park Police and rescue teams from <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Arundel </PERSON>, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> and Prince <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s Counties were dispatched to the scene, along with at least two Medevac helicopters and two rescue buses. Gov. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaefer </PERSON> said he expected the roadway to be opened within 24 hours. `` Everyone's question is why, but it's impossible to tell,'' <PERSON> Schaefer </PERSON> said. `` There is no way in the world I could tell what happened here.'' Investigators from the <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> were on the scene. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON>, deputy administrator for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said an independent investigator would also be brought in. The workers had poured about 120 cubic yards, or 200 tons, of concrete and were about two-thirds of the way through when the bridge collapsed in the middle, <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON> said. They began pouring concrete at 2 a.m. and were being watched by federal inspectors. `` The foreman said he heard a clanging or a clunk just before the bridge collapsed, but there was really no warning,'' <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON> said. He said the supports for the molds into which the concrete was being poured had been inspected and approved in early July.
