<HEAD>Chinese Official Says Gov't to Take Tougher Retrenchment Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice Premier <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilin </PERSON> said Thursday the government will take even tougher retrenchment measures in the next three years to reduce inflation and restore market order. Finance Minister <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingqian </PERSON>, meanwhile, predicted <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s money shortage wil grow more acute next year when more foreign loans start coming due The two officials delivered their sober assessments of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economic situation to the <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the legislature, which began meeting Tuesday <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> said consumer demand continued to grow and many measures intended to cut investment `` did n't work as expected,'' the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. Workers' income is still growing faster than their productivity, he said, and agricultural growth still lags far behind that of industry. `` The government will take tougher measures in the comming three years to accomplish the ongoing economic retrenchment,'' <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> reported. It gave no specifics of what measures would be taken. However, the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported earlier Thursday the government would crack down on illegal trading in key raw materials such as coal and steel, eliminate middlemen in the distribution chain, discipline illegal raw material dealers, and begin an investigation of private businesses to ensure they pay taxes. It quoted <PERSON> Xie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mingan </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Materials </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> as saying efforts would be made to control steel and coal prices and the trend of privatizing distribution of more and more materials would be halted. The government said Monday that any local officials who fail to cut investment will be punished. The government has been trying since September 1988 to reassert many controls over the economy that were weakened or abolished over a decade of reform. Inflation that peaked at about 36 percent _ it now is running at a 25 percent annual rate _ combined with shortages of key materials, hoarding, black marketeering and panic runs on banks triggered the pullback. Measures already taken include orders to cut capital construction, new restrictions on borrowing and government - control of the prices and distribution of some goods <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> told the legislature that the policies had succeeded in cutting industrial growth. Production in the first seven months of the year was up just 10.6 percent from the same period last year, which had been up 17 percent from the year before that. He said bank savings were up. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said state revenue exceeded expenditures over the seven months, although revenue grew more slowly than spending. But both officials spoke gloomily of the future. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> headlined <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>'s report: `` Financial situation dire,'' and quoted <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> as saying <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> faces `` great economic difficulty.'' <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> noted that government subsidies have ballooned in recent years as it has bailed out inefficient state-owned companies, and tried to give farmers a better price for their grain while keeping groceries cheap for urban residents. Borrowing also has accelerated. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s foreign debt, zero in 1978, totaled $ 40 billion at the end of 1988, including $ 10 billion in short-term loans. The government also has borrowed $ 9.3 billion from its own citizens over the past decade by issuing treasury bonds. Many Chinese workers are required to buy the bonds, with the price automatically deducted from their pay. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> blamed the problems on ousted party General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>'s `` errors in financial decisions,'' including violating what he called the `` socialist financial principle'' of balancing the budget. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, who lost his post in a power struggle in June over handling of the spring democracy protests, had advocated rapid growth. Chinese officials have issued repeated assurances recently that the country will be able to repay its debt.
