<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legion </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it has received about 1 million signatures on a petition seeking a constitutional amendment against desecration of the American flag. Senate Republican Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, appearing at a press conference with American Legion national commander <PERSON> H.F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gierke </PERSON>, said legislation calling for the amendment has been scheduled for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor action Oct. 16. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> will consider a bill Sept. 12 that would create a federal law against flag desecration, but not amend the Constitution. `` It's a long process,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said of the amendment route, which requires approval by two-thirds of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and ratification by three-fourths of the states. But, he said, the issue was one that deserved consideration by the states. <PERSON> Gierke </PERSON> said that the legion was getting about 40,000 signatures a day in its nationwide petition drive, which still goes on. `` The constitutional process requires constitutional assurances we'll do the right thing,'' said Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., who also appeared at the news conference Proponents of the amendment say it, rather than a statute, is needed so that the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> will not rule the prohibition unconstitutional. Earlier this year, the court touched off the controversy by deciding that burning the flag was a constitutionally protected form of political protest. Many lawmakers and constitutional law experts oppose the amendment, saying that while emotionally offensive, flag-burning is not a serious enough offense to merit curtailment of free-speech protections. The House bill includes penalties of up to a year in prison plus an unspecified fine for physically desecrating a flag, and was drafted to address the high court's decision that existing statutes against flag burning were an attempt to squelch free speech. Reps. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, who also attended the news conference, said the fight in the House for an amendment would be much tougher than in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. House Majority Leader <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mo </LOCATION>., has said the Democrats want to try a statute before a constitutional amendment to avoid `` adding political graffiti to the Constitution.
