<TEXT>
 The main subgroup of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> urged Thursday that the commission take up the situation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pace </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> human rights spokesman, said it was the first time conditions in one of the five permanent <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> members were referred to the <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The other permanent members are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sates </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. A resolution adopted 15-9, in a secret ballot, by the Sub-Commission on Prevention of Discrimination and the Protection of Minorities expressed concern about recent events in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and `` their consequences in the field of human rights.'' It appealed to <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> authorities for clemency in dealing for those imprisoned after the army brutally suppressed pro-democracy demonstrations in June. The resolution asked the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general `` to transmit to the Commission on Human Rights further information provided by the government of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and other reliable sources.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> rejected the resolution as interference in its internal affairs. <PERSON> Asbjorn </PERSON> <PERSON> Eide </PERSON>, a Norwegian member of the subcommission, described the resolution as `` very conciliatory.'' He said the main purpose was to focus attention on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which includes delegates from 43 governments and will hold its next meeting in February. It is the highest <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> human rights body and can appoint special investigators. A Chinese statement Thursday said: `` This resolution contradicts the purpose of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> charter and runs counter to the norms of governing international relations. The Chinese government rejects this resolution. It is null and void and has no binding force on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> whatsoever.'' The resolution was sponsored by panel members from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Western delegates sought the secret ballot as a means of guarding the independence of the 26-member panel. On Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said at least 1,000 people were killed in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Tiananmen Square when soldiers moved against the unarmed demonstrators June 3-4. It accused the Chinese government of secret executions and mass arrests. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> denied the charges. At a weekly briefing Thursday in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhaoxing </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> claims of a `` wave of repression'' after the crackdown `` are entirely ungrounded and unreasonable.'' `` An extremely small number of people used terrorist means and took violent actions in an attempt to overthrow the legitimate government,'' he said. `` That the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government, according to law, arrested those criminals and sentenced them to imprisonment is entirely legitimate and justified.'' `` No country or organization has the right to interfere in an issue that is purely another country's internal affair.''
