<HEAD>USDA Lending Agency to Get Tough, Yeutter Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said Thursday the <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has turned from being a lender into a `` grant agency'' and that he is determined to put it on a more business-like footing. `` We've just got to reform that program, take it out of the status of what it's really become _ a grant agency _ and move it back to being a credit institution once again,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. The FmHA has its roots in the Great Depression of the 1930s and is often called the government's farm lender of last resort. To be eligible for loans, farmers must be unable to get regular loans from banks or other commercial institutions. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> agency has `` made billions of dollars of questionable loans over the last decade or so, many of which are in default today.'' But he noted that attempts have been made to change <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> and to toughen its lending practices, only to be thwarted by legal action filed by farmers or their advocates, or by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` If we have to change legislation in this area in order to do a more effective and skillful job of managing -LRB- FmHA -RRB-, we'll make legislative proposals to have that happen,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> told a television news conference. `` If we can do it administratively ... we'll do it that way.'' For years, the <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> has been embroiled in controversial attempts to collect long-overdue farm loans. New procedures to help protect the interests of farmers and to enable the agency to proceed with its collections were included by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the Agricultural Credit Act of 1987. The latest move involves FmHA sending out a new batch of collection notices to borrowers who failed to make their scheduled payments by the first of this year. Agency spokesman <PERSON> Marlyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Aycock </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION>'s county offices were told to mail out the collection notices by Aug. 25 so that delinquent borrowers could have them by Sept. 1. The county offices were sent lists of delinquents totaling 13,217 borrowers as of Aug. 1 and were instructed to delete names of those who had settled their accounts since then. <PERSON> Aycock </PERSON> said those deletions possibly could reduce the list to between 11,000 and 12,000 names by the time they were mailed out last week. `` But we wo n't get an actual count until farther down the road,'' he said. The list of delinquencies has shrunk dramatically since Jan. 1 when it was more than 30,000 borrowers he said. By July 3 it was down to 15,704 names, and the Aug. 1 count dropped to 13,217 _ the basic list sent to county offices. Borrowers will have 45 days from receipt of the notices to return forms to FmHA describing how they want to settle their overdue accounts. The 1987 law requires the agency to tell farmers they have certain options, including reamortization or rescheduling, payment deferral, reduced interest rates and, in some cases, debt forgiveness. If farmers do not respond, or if a borrower is in such poor financial shape that no alternative can be worked out, forced sale or foreclosure proceedings could begin. <PERSON> Aycock </PERSON> said the latest notices are in addition to more than 66,000 sent out last fall to delinquent borrowers, many of whom had not made payments for three years or more. The total owed FmHA by all delinquent borrowers is around $ 8.7 billion, although there is no breakdown showing how much the 1989 notices involve, he said.
