<HEAD>Federal Wildlife Officials to Split Whooping Crane Colony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUREL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wildlife officials will split the only captive colony of endangered whooping cranes to reduce the chances of disease or disaster wiping out the flock. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said this week that 22 of the 54 birds at the <ORGANIZATION> Patuxent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> will be sent in November to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baraboo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION> `` The service has been concerned about having all of their eggs in one basket, literally,'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Trauger </PERSON>, the Patuxent center's deputy director `` The service felt it was the prudent thing to do, to separate the breeding flocks, and there's enough breeders now to do that.'' The center started in 1987 to breed the rare birds, known for their elaborate courtship dance, under a joint program with Canadian wildlife officials. A wild flock of the cranes migrates to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> for the winter from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, 2,400 miles away. This year, 138 made the migration. Before conservation efforts began, there were only 21 whooping cranes in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> in the winter. Scientists hope that by breeding whooping cranes in captivity, they will be able to establish another flock in the wild.
