<HEAD>Bush, Mulroney Discuss Trade and Fishery Issues, Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES with news conference; new thruout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Canadian Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said today they stand ready, in <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s words, to help <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> `` stomp out'' the terror of drugs In a seaside news conference at <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s vacation home, the two leaders chatted about what <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called `` an unusually productive visit,'' that included airing differences on two trade issues: lobsters and pork. But the two leaders, both casually dressed, directed most of their attention to international issues, including ongoing efforts to oust <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> dictator <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. On the situation in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has thwarted the scheduled transition to democracy, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> acknowledged feeling `` a high frustration level'' with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to dislodge the dictator. But he added: `` We are not going to give up on this. We are not going to permit the will of the people of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to be thwarted by this dictator.''. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` I've never seen a coming together in world opinion as there is on this one ... that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> ought to get out.'' After the two leaders concluded their 35-minute news conference, White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> predicted the president's new anti-drug package will cost $ 7.8 billion _ almost $ 2 billion above current spending levels. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will unveil it on Tuesday. Asked whether he favored use of a multilateral military to help <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> wipe out the drug cartels, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> replied, `` The main thing is to cooperate with President -LRB- <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> in the ways that he feels -LRB- would be -RRB- most effective.' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> added, `` There is no point on <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or ... any group of countries imposing its will on a country that is now trying very, very hard to rid itself of this menace.'' <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> were in `` complete agreement ... -LRB- on -RRB- the need to support a very courageous leader in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and the need to stomp out by every reasonable means the terror of drugs.'' While <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said there was `` broad'' agreement between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> on trade, `` there are still bumps in the road.'' Asked whether he favored a multilateral force to fight <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s drug cartels, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he did n't want to `` do something or say something that would be counterproductive and turn public opinion ... against President <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>'s efforts. But he said `` an international effort on whatever line it is _ aid, help of any kind _ would be useful.' On the lobster dispute, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said: `` The president was big on lobsters today. I was big on pork because we feel that the Americans have just imposed an unfair tariff on pork.'' He said they had discussed the mechanisms to resolve the pork dispute under the Free Trade Agreement. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` advanced some persuasive arguments that I have instructed my officials to begin examining'' on the lobsters. <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> lobstermen say the Canadians catch lobsters so small they have not even had a chance to reproduce. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, who leaves with his family later today, said they had been swimming, boating, and doing other activities, including `` a little fishing by me.'' <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> throughout his 16 days here on vacation, caught nothing. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> offered `` the impartial international assessment of the fact that there are no fish out there. I can certify to that. It's not the president's fault. On another issue, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he was considering increasing emergency food shipments to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. `` That is one -LRB- area -RRB- where we ought to be able to do more,'' he said.
