<HEAD>Election Weighed in Reagan Administration Homeless Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration official last year urged repeal of a program to assist the homeless, but several <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> officials warned against such a move in an election year, according to documents released Thursday. `` Such an effort would undoubtedly be unsuccessful and could unfortunately be interpreted as a lack of in interest in the plight of the homeless by this department, thus subjecting the secretary and the administration to strong criticism of a politically sensitive and visible issue during an election year,'' one <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> official wrote in response to the recommendation from then Social Security Commissioner <PERSON> Dorcas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>. In that memo, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Docksai </PERSON>, then the department's assistant secretary for legislation, also warned that it would be `` politically untenable'' to attempt to repeal the program, under which the government was to fund efforts to screen the homeless population for people eligible for Social Security. The memo in which <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> made the recommendation to then-HHS Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> and a number of subsequent internal HHS memos discussing the idea were released by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homelessness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poverty </ORGANIZATION>, which had criticized the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for not implementing the program. The documents show that while several <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> officials appeared to agree with <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON>'s recommendation, they did not believe <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would agree to the repeal and also suspected that even suggesting such a move would hurt the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> in last year's presidential election. The law center obtained the documents under the Freedom of Information Act. `` We agree that the department should not seek an appropriation for the program,'' Assistant Secretary for Health <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON> wrote in an April 1988 memo. `` However, if we actively work to repeal the legislation, the administration risks being portrayed as uncaring for the homeless. Since nothing is happening at the moment, silence seems the best policy given the politics of homeless issues.'' In a letter to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, the advocacy group said the program still has not been funded. `` This policy is reprehensible; it is also illegal,'' <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Foscarinis </PERSON> of the law center said in the letter to <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. `` I ask that you reverse this policy by implementing the outreach program at once.'' A <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> spokesman did not immediately return a telephone message left Thursday. The program was authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1987. It was designed to create an HHS-administered pilot program under which the federal government would provide money to state and local governments that established teams to identify homeless people potentially eligible for Social Security benefits. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> authorized $ 3.75 million for the program and said up to $ 1 million should be taken from <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> surplus funds to pay for implementation of the program.
