<HEAD>Five Winners Receive Magsaysay Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An American Jesuit priest who was jailed by <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> for criticizing the government said Thursday the church's greatest recent achievement was helping oust the former president. The Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertram </PERSON> <PERSON> Reuter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, made the remarks during ceremonies at which he was awarded the 1989 Ramon Magsaysay Prize for journalism, literature and creative communications arts. A Malaysian, an Indian, a South Korean and a technological school in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> also were honored by the <ORGANIZATION> Magsaysay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. The awards were presented Thursday by the Foundation on the 82nd birthday of the late President <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Magsaysay </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` The most spectacular contribution of the Church to the world in recent years, through media, was EDSA,'' said <PERSON> Reuter </PERSON>, referring to a highway where mutinous soldiers took control of the military's headquarters to start a four-day revolt that toppled <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and propelled <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to the presidency `` It was the first revolution in history to be run by radio,'' <ORGANIZATION> Reuter </ORGANIZATION> added. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> led by <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>'s Archbishop Cardinal <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Sin </PERSON> called on the people to march in the streets as a sign of support for the rebellious soldiers Sin's call was made over the church's radio station <ORGANIZATION> Veritas </ORGANIZATION>. Troops loyal to <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> destroyed the Church's transmitter but the radio station continued airing information about the revolt using another radio station. `` It was an accident of history that the Church was in position at that time,'' <ORGANIZATION> Reuter </ORGANIZATION> said. `` we had the equipment. We had the personnel. We had the organization. And we had the courage to do it.'' Reuter, who has lived in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> for more than 40 years, ran a weekly newsletter that had been critical of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> rule. When martial law was declared in 1972, the newspaper was closed and he was placed under house arrest for two years. The other winners were Zakiah Hanum binti <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamid </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> for government service, <PERSON> Sri </PERSON> <PERSON> Lakshmi </PERSON> <PERSON> Chand </PERSON> <PERSON> Jain </PERSON> of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> for public service, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Im-soon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> for community leadership, and the <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>. Each winner received a gold medallion, a scroll and $ 30,000.
