<HEAD>Pilot's License Now Easier to Obtain, Despite Objections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New regulations designed to make it easier and less expensive to learn to fly went into effect Thursday over the objections of federal air safety regulators and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The new rule would permit issuance of a so-called recreational pilot's license after only 30 hours of flight instruction, compared with the 40 required for a regular license. The recreational license will permit pilots to fly only within 50 miles of the airport where they learned to fly. They may fly only in the daytime and in clear weather and may not use airports with traffic control towers. `` We are hoping this is going to provide a stepping stone,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` People are going to get into aviation as a result of this, because it is going to be less expensive.'' <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> hopes many of them will then go on to get a regular pilot's certificate, helping to fill a growing shortage of airline pilots. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauber </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, said the board has long opposed the new license. `` I am in sympathy with the problem we have of getting more people involved in aviation,'' <PERSON> Lauber </PERSON> said. `` It's just that I'm not convinced that that's the right way to go about it.'' `` I do wonder how they can adequately enforce the many restrictions that have been put on,'' he said. The new rule was first proposed in 1979. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> estimates it will reduce the cost of learning to fly by as much as 39 percent, from about $ 3,000 to less than $ 2,000. The license will limit the pilot to planes with no more than four seats and 180-horsepower engines. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, director of engineering and air safety for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the association plans to renew its objections to the new rule, which is still subject to revision. `` It does cost an awful lot for a young person coming up through the ranks to try to get a private pilot's license today,'' <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said. `` And if there is any means of reducing the cost of that license, then we might provide more pilots and a larger demand for airlines and a larger group of pilots for the airlines to select from.'' `` This seems to make sense, except that by getting a recreational license you certainly are n't getting the kind of training necessary to go on to flying with the airlines or making yourself a good, safe, sane pilot,'' he said.
