<HEAD>Veteran CBS Newsman Robert Schakne Dies at 63</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Emmy award-winning <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> newsman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Schakne </PERSON>, who covered civil rights, war, political scandal and revolution during a 39-year career, died Thursday of cancer, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said. He was 63. <PERSON> Schakne </PERSON>, who died at <LOCATION> Sibley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> here, worked at <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> for 33 years, covering such major stories as the Iran-Contra arms and money scandal, the Watergate trials, the investigation of the Challenger space shuttle disaster and the Vietnam War. He won a national Emmy for his reporting on the grand jury investigation of former Vice President <PERSON> Spiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> and his resignation from office. `` For decades, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Schakne </PERSON> set the highest standards in our profession,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. `` He was a sensitive man with great class and intelligence, and the people of <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> are indebted to him for his enormous contributions and achievements.'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stringer </PERSON>, president, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> @ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, called <PERSON> Schakne </PERSON> `` a reporter's reporter _ dogged in pursuit of the truth and committed to the craft of careful reporting. His professionalism, his precision and, perhaps above all, his integrity, will be long remembered and treasured at <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>.'' Prior to joining <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Schakne </PERSON> was employed by the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> bureau </ORGANIZATION> <