<HEAD>July Prices Paid to Farmers Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices farmers got for raw products dropped 1.4 percent from July to August, leaving the monthly average at a year-ago level, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said in its preliminary report that lower prices for soybeans, corn, lettuce and potatoes were mostly responsible for the decrease from the July average. Higher prices for cattle, apples, eggs and grapefruit partly offset the decline for the other commodities. Oilseeds, which include soybeans, and feed grains showed the greatest month-to-month decline, while meat animals and milk had the largest increases. `` A 90-cents-per-bushel decline in the price of soybeans from July to August was the largest month-to-month decline since June-July 1984,'' the report said. `` Corn and sorghum prices were down but the average barley price was up.'' Wheat prices moved up after four months of small declines. Hogs and beef cattle were up from July, but calf prices were down slightly. Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said earlier Thursday that he expects 1989 will be `` a good year'' for farmers, although there is `` a mixed situation across the country'' because of drought and other weather problems. `` I would guess net cash income -LRB- nationally -RRB- would be slightly below 1988, but not very much below,'' he said. Crop production generally has rebounded from last year's drought-reduced yields and exports are up. `` Overall, I'd say farmers feel a lot better,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. Department economists say net cash income of farmers _ gross cash income minus cash expenses _ rose in 1988 to a record of about $ 60 billion as drought forced commodity prices up. Many producers were able to sell harvests at the higher prices, thus more than offsetting reduced production. The decline this year is expected to stem from farmers' larger cash expenses as they boost plantings, and also because of lower federal subsidies. Consumer food prices are forecast by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> to rise an average of 5 percent to 7 percent this year, following a 4.1 percent increase in 1988. Based on the preliminary figures, the price index for livestock and livestock products as a group increased 1.9 percent from July and averaged 5.3 percent above the year-earlier level. Crop prices, overall, dropped 4.5 percent from July and averaged 5.9 percent less than in August 1988. The all-fruit price index for August was up 8.8 percent from July but was down 4.9 percent from a year ago, the report said. Apples were reported at 16.1 cents per pound, compared with 9.8 cents in July. A year ago apples were 24.5 cents per pound. Grapefruit prices averaged $ 7.24 per box, compared with $ 4.62 in July and $ 4.09 a year earlier. As used in the report, a box of grapefruit is about 67 pounds. Prices of commercial vegetables dropped 15 percent from July, averaging 6.5 percent below a year ago, the report said. The overall index of prices paid to farmers in July averaged 144 percent of a 1977 base used for comparison, down from 146 percent in July. That was the lowest reading since November when the index was also 144 percent. The report said: _ Cattle averaged $ 69.60 per 100 pounds of live weight nationally, up from $ 68 in July and $ 65.90 in August 1988 Those are averages for all types of cattle sold as bee. _ Hogs averaged $ 46.10 per 100 pounds, compared with $ 45.90 in July and $ 44.70 a year earlier _ Corn, at $ 2.29 a bushel, was down from $ 2.47 in July and $ 2.65 in August 1988 _ Wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures, averaged $ 3.83 per bushel, compared with $ 3.78 in July and $ 3.61 a year earlier _ Rice averaged $ 7.20 per 100 pounds, down from $ 7.33 in July and $ 7.43 a year earlier _ Soybeans were $ 5.93 per bushel, compared with $ 6.83 in July and $ 8.33 a year earlier _ Upland cotton was reported at 64.3 cents per pound, up from 60.6 in July and 53.9 in August 1988 _ Eggs were 71 cents per dozen, up from 64 cents in July and 58.1 cents a year earlier _ Milk was $ 12.90 per 100 pounds, compared with $ 12.60 in July and $ 11.80 a year earlier _ Broilers were 36.1 cents per pound, live weight, down from 39.1 cents in July and 42.3 cents a year ago
