 </LOCATION> fell out with <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in 1972 when <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> spurned <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s proposal to merge their countries Relations deteriorated as <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> pursued his peace policy and rapprochement with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> blamed <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> for bombings in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION> and other cities in 1975 and 1976, which led to the war. Since <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> took office in 1981, <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> envoys have embarked on more than a dozen futile secret missions to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> publicly said they always brought expressions of friendship, yet each trip was followed by hostile Libyan actions. That was before this spring's summit in <LOCATION> Casablanca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>. On May 23, <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> met there and agreed to bury the hatchet. About relations with <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> told the Yugoslav news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> in an interview published Thursday: `` They are improving steadily. There is no problem there.'' He added embassy buildings in the respective capitals `` are being prepared,'' but did not say when he expects resumed diplomatic relations. A senior government official, who demanded anonymity, said <PERSON> Waly </PERSON>'s trip `` underlines the two countries' common desire to reinforce and normalize relations. But on restoring diplomatic ties, he said: `` It's up to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> are the only two to hold out among 17 <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states that broke with <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> between December 1978 and the following April because of the treaty with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <LOC