<HEAD>Much To Celebrate On Solidarity's Ninth Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GDA50</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 10,000 Poles roared their applause as <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> joined them Thursday to celebrate the ninth anniversary of the birth of Solidarity and pray for the success of the new Solidarity-led government. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and Solidarity, the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's first independent trade union, had much to celebrate this year. The union emerged from seven years of banishment to end 45 years of communist control of the Polish government. `` On Aug. 31, 1980, I signed in your name the document which became the basis for the creation of Solidarity and which changed the course of Polish history,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> told his cheering supporters. `` We reject the road of violence and revolution, but we have the right to use legal measures. We want to have a government really capable of changing <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and really responsible in front of Solidarity and its allies and in front of the nation. `` It is our duty to make sure that is what happens. Remember at the end, it is always the nation, the ordinary people, who decide.'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, a shipyard electrician and 1983 Nobel Peace laureate, drew cheers as he took his seat in front of the towering workers monument in front of the <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION>, where Solidarity was born. Sitting next to <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> was a special guest, <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON>, the `` Courier from <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>,'' who smuggled information out of Nazi-occupied <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> during World War II and who long headed the Polish section of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government-financed Radio Free <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, becoming an enemy of the communist state for his uncensored broadcasts. Solidarity's <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>, who became prime minister last week, said in a television address he could not join the <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> commemoration because of the pressing need to form his new government. Dozens of delegations from mines and factories across <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> dipped Solidarity flags at the monument honoring workers killed during 1970 workers' riots along the Baltic coast. Two parachutes lettered with `` Solidarity'' fluttered from poles near the shipyard entrance. Exactly one year ago, the shipyard was strikebound for the second time in four months and <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> for his first talks in six years with communist authorities desperate for a solution to nationwide labor unrest. Later that day, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> and successfully appealed for an end to the strikes. His discussions with authorities led to the start in February of talks on political and economic reform. After the historic negotiations came restoration of Solidarity's legal status April 17 and June elections that were the freest in the Soviet bloc in four decades Solidarity's stunning victories and the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s disastrous showings led to the unprecedented possibility of power-sharing And on Aug. 24, as a result of a parliamentary coalition forged by <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> between Solidarity and two smaller parties long allied with the Communists, <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> became prime minister. `` We enter a new epoch. It depends on us when we will be able to say <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is a free, democratic and wealthy country. Now I say that next year, we will be thankful for visible economic acheivements,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> said over TV, `` I very warmly greet all my friends from those times that we spent together in such hard, dramatic, but I think fruitful, circumstances. I am with them during these solemn ceremonies.'' <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON> was overcome by emotion as he stood to address the assemblage. He returned to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> on Tuesday for the first time since fleeing at the end of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Uprising of 1944. `` It seems absolutely impossible I can stand in front of you,'' <PERSON> Nowak </PERSON> said. `` Solidarity, although defenseless, opened a road to me for my own country with its spirit. `` Not so long ago, what I would have faced here would have been a death sentence.'' An outdoor Mass was celebrated by <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> Bishop <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Goclowski </PERSON>, who wore robes embroidered with `` Solidarity'' in red glitter. `` Today we can be real co-partners in truth, be those who will build the new reality of our homeland,'' <PERSON> Goclowski </PERSON> said. Piles of bouquets, two framed photos of Polish-born Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II and a wooden cross decorated the main gate of the <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION>. Even the <ORGANIZATION> Gdansk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <PERSON> Glos </PERSON> <PERSON> Wybrzeza </PERSON> marked the anniversary in a front page article under the headline `` Hope.'' `` Almost all of us remember that day ... From August 1980, not only nine years have passed, an epoch has passed. Especially the recent months were filled with changes that stunned the world,'' the paper said.
