<TEXT>
 A leading private environmental group said Thursday the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> was not doing enough to help Third World countries combat the threat of rising global temperatures. The bank, owned by 151 governments, is the largest source of aid to the Third World, lending over $ 19 billion a year. `` The status quo is not acceptable as an option,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON>, senior attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. His criticism was based on an internal bank paper prepared in advance of a major speech on the environment that the bank's president, <ORGANIZATION> Barber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conable </ORGANIZATION>, is due to deliver in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Sept. 11 The paper includes a section entitled: `` The Bank Can Do More.'' `` This document is the equivalent of saying that hats and sunglasses will solve the problem of stratospheric ozone destruction,'' <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON> said in a statement on the paper. One threat to the environment foreseen by some scientists is that chemicals released on Earth are destroying the layer of ozone, a gas in the upper atmosphere that protects the planet from harmful rays of the sun. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogl </PERSON>, the bank's chief spokesman, said the paper was only one of many inputs for <PERSON> Conable </PERSON>'s speech and for a new `` operational directive'' the bank is preparing. `` The statements of a tiny number of environmentalists fail to acknowledge the immense volume of undertakings by the bank,'' he said in an interview.
