<HEAD>Former Noriega Classmate Named Provisional President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A council controlled by Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> named one of his high school classmates as provisional president Thursday and said the timing of new elections depends on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> _ Cabinet ministers and heads of agencies and the military _ chose <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> to head the government and said elections could not be held until <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic sanctions and `` aggression'' ended. It said the situation will be evaluated in six months to determine whether elections are possible. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who holds the real power in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> as head of the military and police, is a member of the council and is presumed to control it. He and <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> were close friends in high school and graduated in 1957. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, who has spent most of his life as a government administrator, takes office Friday when acting President <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>'s term ends. <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> finished the term of <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, who was dismissed after trying to fire <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> last year as chief of <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> still recognizes <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>. International observers said the opposition candidate won the May 7 presidential elections by a 3-1 margin, but the government annulled the vote on grounds the results were `` distorted'' by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interference and economic aid to the opposition. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has imposed economic sanctions on <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in an effort to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who has been indicted in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on federal charges of drug trafficking and money laundering. At a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, Deputy Secretary of State <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> said <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was a man of `` shameless excess,'' who amassed a fortune of up to $ 300 million from drugs and other criminal activities. <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> made the allegation in response to a challenge from a <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> diplomat last week for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to back up charge charges. Chosen as provisional vice president of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozores </PERSON> <PERSON> Typaldos </PERSON>, a leader of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and deputy director of the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estrella </ORGANIZATION>. The Council of State said the national legislature would be abolished and the government would rule with a legislative commission of 41 appointed members. It said the government would rule by decree until the commission was selected. City governments will be replaced by appointed officials and the new government will draft a new constitution, the council said. `` <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> has lived a historic moment today as a free and sovereign nation and within its laws,'' <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> said after the announcement that his friend would become president. Political opposition leaders have called the new government `` a continuation of the military dictatorship.'' <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> said <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> was chosen `` because of the knowledge he has of the country's economic situation and balanced judgment he has exercised in his decisions.'' <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is in an economic crisis aggravated by the two-year confrontation with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. According to the comptroller's office, the gross national product declined 17 per cent in 1988, the worst drop since 1945, and more than 30,000 jobs were lost. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has has withheld fees for use of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> since March 1988, has stopped payment of taxes on salaries of <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> employees and has frozen <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> government funds in American banks. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say normal relations can not be resumed with a government <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> controls. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> claims the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> plans to kidnap the general. Sandbagged fortifications have been built around the headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> and other military installations. Military units of the two countries have been had several confrontations in which, as a diplomat put it, `` they have come pretty close to shooting.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has military installations in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and is charged with protecting the canal until the end of 1999, when it will be turned over to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> claims the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> charges against him are part of a plot to renege on the 1977 treaties and keep the canal.
