<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Delegates and experts predict more factional warfare in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> now that an international conference has failed to produce a peace plan. `` The moment is favorable'' for a period of military testing, <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> specialist <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Godement </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday. `` The question is at what level of intensity.'' An overriding concern at the monthlong conference, which ended Wednesday in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, was that civil war would resume when <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> pulled its forces out Sept. 27, leaving the army of Premier <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> to fend for itself. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in December 1978 and overthrew the brutal <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> regime of <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON>, which was held responsible for 1 million deaths during less than four years in power. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Naruedol </PERSON> <PERSON> Dejpradiyuth </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> army spokesman, said Thursday in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> he doubted the Vietnamese pullout would be complete but still expected a renewal of the war in neighboring <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. He spoke at the monthly army news conference. A Vietnamese radio broadcast said guerrillas encamped near the border already were trying to push soldiers and civilians into the Cambodian interior `` to provide a legal status for the so-called resistance ... before a cease-fire takes effect and elections are held.'' Delegates and observers note the Vietnamese departure comes at the beginning of the dry season, the traditional time for intensified combat in <LOCATION> C