est of political opinion, things will go back to ... the battlefield.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration welcomed the progress made at the conference and hoped it would lead to a comprehensive settlement. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Mai </PERSON>, Vietnamese ambassador in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>'s army was capable of defending itself. `` They are very self-confident and I think they are very capable,'' he said. At a news conference Wednesday night, <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> called for a diplomatic solution but said he expected renewed attacks by the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have really prepared ourselves for the worst,'' he told the reporters.
