<TEXT>
 A seven-pronged, $ 191 million research program to understand how man's activities and pollution are changing the planet was laid out Thursday by a group of federal agencies. The goal is `` to monitor, understand and, ultimately, predict global change,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Post </PERSON> of the Office of Science and Technology Policy. `` Global change is a large, complex scientific problem and it still is not largely understood,'' said <PERSON> Dallas </PERSON> <PERSON> Peck </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> U. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION> and chairman of the federal <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>, which is coordinating the research effort. `` There is a shared, common purpose; to understand global change. We're in the planning stages,'' added <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The effort announced Thursday covers the coming fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. <PERSON> Peck </PERSON> described it as largely a planning period to be used setting up research programs likely to last a decade or more. The atmosphere and the role of clouds received top priority in in the program. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said clouds are a major factor in the feared rise in global temperatures, and their effect is not well understood. The widely discussed threat of global warming, however, is only part of the overall research effort. The studies also will look at threats to the earth's protective ozone layer, possible changes in the oceans and atmosphere, air pollution, acid rain and other processes. Reports of warmer temperatures have drawn the most attention recently. Some scientists are concerned that carbon dioxide and other gases added to the atmosphere by human activities are causing the higher temperatures and tha eventually they might lead to disruptive climate changes. Other scientists dispute the so-called greenhouse effect, and evidence is lacking on both sides. That is an area the researchers hope to tackle early. Funds totaling $ 191.5 million for fiscal 1990 are included in the budgets of various departments to get the program under way, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Corell </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. In January the committee will put together requests for funds for 1991 and future years, he said. The seven major areas of research set forth Thursday are: _ Climate and hydrologic systems The role of clouds is the first item on the agenda, followed by research in ocean circulation, and interaction of the air land and water. _ Biogeochemical dynamics: the relationship between living organisms and the water and atmosphere For example, trees take carbon dioxide out of the air and replace it with oxygen. Cutting down trees reduces that activity. _ Ecological systems and dynamics: how people, plants and animals would react to climate change and how those reactions might in turn affect other processes _ Earth system history: what has happened to the land, air and water when climate has changed in the past _ Human interactions: population growth and development, energy and land use and industrial production and how those activities affect the earth _ Solid earth research: coastal erosion, volcanoes and their effect on climate, permafrost, the seafloor and other areas _ Solar influences: monitoring incoming radiation from the sun, the amount reflected back into space and how this energy affects the earth and its climate In addition to the Geological Survey, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION>, other agencies in the program are the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, Council on Environmental Quality and the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
