<HEAD>Supreme Court Suspends Adoptions by Foreign Families</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday suspended the adoptions of babies by foreigners after President <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> complained the system was run more like a business than a social service. Court President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Correa </PERSON> said adoptions in process may be completed. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> complained publicly on Aug. 17 that `` infants are being sold for $ 7,000 and incredibly, judges and lawyers are involved in this business. ... It is a shame that Paraguayan children are negotiated over like merchandise.'' The general ousted the 34-year regime of President Gen. <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> in a Feb. 3 coup and was overwhelmingly elected president on May 1. Newspapers printed stories involving poor women who said they felt pressured to give up their children, and of foreigners, many from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, allegedly paying large sums for healthy babies with blond hair and blue eyes. Judges became reluctant to give the final authorization that would allow Paraguayan infants to leave the country with adoptive parents. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> and <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinhof </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, are among eight <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> couples in <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION> awaiting judicial permission to take home babies they were given since arriving during the previous two weeks. `` <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> has put on 1 -LCB- pounds since we got him,'' <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinhof </PERSON>, a 36-year-old computer software salesman, said in a telephone interview. `` They asked us what color we wanted,'' he said, noting that the baby has `` dark hair, dark eyes and medium to dark skin ... We did n't care. We were more concerned that it be a boy. We have a daughter.'' Until recently, adoptions by foreign families were comparatively easy and fast. Adoptions by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> families went from 37 in 1985 to 322 in 1988. `` I called several adoption agencies in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, but when they found out our ages, they would n't accept us,'' said <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooper </PERSON>, 37, in an interview earlier this year. She and her husband, <PERSON> Granville </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooper </PERSON>, 40, of <LOCATION> Hanceville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, now are the parents of 6-month-old <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>, a chubby, black-haired boy with brown eyes. About 220 adoptions are pending, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> official said in a telephone interview. The official, who commented on condition of anonymity, said it was unclear how many would be allowed to go through. Under regulations due to be revised, preference was given to Paraguayans seeking to adopt and foreign families had to submit eight reports during the first two years to document their child's progress The maximum age was 60 instead of 45, as is the limit in many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> states, and there were fewer obstacles to adoptions by single parents. Most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> applications included an approval from a stateside adoption agency or social worker, and a visa from the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> that allowed the child to enter the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Steinhof </PERSON> said he thought public opposition to the adoptions was based on misconceptions. `` They seem to think we come on a plane on Tuesday, pay someone and leave with a kid on Wednesday.''
