<HEAD>Congressman Says Contras Cannot Be Monitored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressman opposed to aid for <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> Contras contended Thursday the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> admits it lacks the intelligence capability to assure that rebel attacks on civilians in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> had ceased. `` The adminstration admits now that they knew that they could n't keep their promise to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people,'' Rep. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON> said in a news release that quoted a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> letter to him <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON> was referring to the agreement under which the Contras could receive non-military aid if they refrained from offensive actions. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, however, said its letter was misinterpreted. The letter from <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for legislative affairs, said: `` We do not have a strong intelligence capability to assess responsibility for the initiation of the reported clashes which mar the informal truce in effect between the Nicaraguan Resistance and Sandinista forces. `` But given that the Resistance has been cut off from military aid and is very low on ammunition, we do not believe that they have the ability to take an offensive mode.'' Ms. <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> said the department has asserted to the Contras its position against military attacks. `` In one case, we terminated family support to a commander whose unit initiated an offensive operation after the bipartisan accord,'' she said. She also said `` we may have prevented an offensive operation'' in another instance, by contacting the Contra command after learning a unit leader may have been planning an attack. The letter was a response to one written by <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON> and signed by 83 members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> asking the administration to investigate allegations that the Contras were `` engaged in offensive military actions.'' <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON>'s letter listed nine alleged Contra attacks between April 13 and June 8, reported by Witness for Peace, a human rights organization. The congressman said the reports have been corroborated by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> journalists. `` The administration is turning a blind eye to a series of well-documented human rights abuses and military actions by Contra forces,'' said <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON>' response did not speak directly to the Witness for Peace list, but alluded to another series of alleged Contra attacks reported by the Nicaraguan government which, she said, were investigated by an agency. She did not identify the agency but said that it could verify only a small number as having taken place. On the other hand, she said: `` The Department has received an increasing number of worrisome reports of Sandinista abuses from Nicaraguan and international human rights organizations.'' Under the bipartisan agreement that accompanied the $ 48 million Contra aid package approved last April, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> promised to cut off funds to all <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> units that persisted in offensive actions such as killing or kidnaping civilians. Under the informal agreement, which has no legal standing, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he would not continue spending the $ 48 million on the Contras after Nov. 30 if congressional leaders found that the Contras were not acting in good faith toward peace in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The money was appropriated for use through Feb. 28, 1990.
