<TEXT>
 The historic Lower Pontalba Apartments sustained no structural damage when three stories of scaffolding collapsed during renovation of the French Quarter landmark, an architect reported Thursday. The scaffolding on the 138-year-old structure, regarded as the nation's first apartment building, collapsed Aug. 23 into Jackson Square. There were no injuries reported. Architect <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said balconies on the second and third floors were damaged in the collapse, some third-floor timbers also need to be shored up, and bricks and stone in the attic should be stored on the ground floor. It was the second spectacular Jackson Square accident in 16 months. In May 1988, fire destroyed the top floor of the nearby Cabildo, where the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Purchase </LOCATION> territories were transferred from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
