<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Princess <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> is to separate from her husband <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> after 15 years of marriage, his father said, but there were conflicting reports of whether the royal couple would divorce. A Buckingham Palace press officer refused to comment on a statement Wednesday night by Maj. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> that <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>, 39, and his son, 40, will separate but said a palace announcement would be issued today. Maj. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> denied the couple was divorcing but <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> reported that the palace planned such an announcement. The palace press officer, who in accordance with British practice spoke on condition of anonymity, also refused comment on the TV report. Rumors of trouble in the marriage of Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>'s only daughter date to 1981. In recent years <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> and <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> have spent periods of up to six months apart.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State and local governments face increasingly difficult budget choices as the growing AIDS epidemic siphons more of their resources, according to a privately financed survey. Most states continue to rely heavily on federal money to support AIDS programs, but nine _ including <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> _ are spending more of their own funds this year than they are getting in federal grants. Additionally, states further down in the ranking of cumulative AIDS cases are increasing their spending to battle the disease by 10-fold or more, said the survey by the AIDS Policy Center at the <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` AIDS is going to increase the budgetary tradeoffs the states must make,'' said <PERSON> Mona </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON>, who helped conduct the survey paid for by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for AIDS Research.
</TEXT>
