<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:EdinburghFestival Adv04   08-31 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Edinburgh Festival, Adv 04,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, Sept 4 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>American Bombs Light Up the Edinburgh Fringe</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Cristofer is CQ in 3rd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two plays that flopped in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> are delighting critics and audiences at the <ORGANIZATION> Edinburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fringe </ORGANIZATION>, vindicating the faith of a producer with a fondness for `` problem plays.'' To be sure, the 422 plays on offer in the 43rd annual Festival Fringe include the usual number of American classics and Broadway hits, from `` Long Day's Journey Into Night'' to more recent works including `` Agnes of God'' and `` Night, <PERSON> Mother </PERSON>.'' But two plays that were original also-rans are unexpectedly coming up trumps: <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Albee </PERSON>'s `` The Man Who Had Three Arms'' and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristofer </PERSON>'s `` The Lady and the Clarinet.'' Both plays, which were <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> flops in the early 1980s, have won The Scotsman newspaper's coveted Fringe First awards, given weekly to the best of the Fringe's many openings during the Festival's three weeks. `` <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> is a place where people feel able to see stuff over again, to make a re-evaluation,'' said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Easton </PERSON>, the New York-based producer of `` Lady and the Clarinet.'' The play, about the amorous foibles of a woman named <PERSON> Luba </PERSON>, starred <PERSON> Stockard </PERSON> <PERSON> Channing </PERSON> in its off-Broadway production in 1983. This time, with British actress <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON> <PERSON> Staunton </PERSON> as <PERSON> Luba </PERSON>, the play is selling out at the 72-seat Netherbow Center playhouse. On Sept. 12, it transfers to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s King's Head Theater for a month, with a further transfer to the commercial West End likely to follow. `` It's not <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>; it's not great social drama. -LRB- But -RRB- it is more than just a funny play,'' said <PERSON> Easton </PERSON>, who believes the play was undervalued in its <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> debut. `` I was surprised it had n't fared better there. <PERSON> Easton </PERSON> has been at the Fringe for eight years as executive producer of the American Festival Theater, a producing organization devoted to a cross-section of American plays. `` I've always liked to take on problem plays _ plays that have n't had whatever reception you think they should have had,'' he said Critics in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> have reaffirmed his faith in <PERSON> Cristofer </PERSON>, who is at work on the screenplay of <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>'s novel `` Bonfire of the Vanities.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> in The Sunday Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> called `` Lady'' a `` spick-and-span little play, brilliantly acted by everyone.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Coveney </PERSON> in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> thought it `` zippy,'' and said <PERSON> Staunton </PERSON> was `` wonderful.'' <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON>, director of the Southside International production of <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Albee </PERSON>'s `` Man Who Had Three Arms,'' similarly refused to be swayed by her play's previous fate. `` I think this is an exciting, really wonderful play,'' said <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON>, a professor of English at <ORGANIZATION> Albright </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in Reading, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>. She described her contribution as `` getting the play out of the drawer,'' following its frosty Broadway reception in 1983 <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON> first mounted the three-character play at an Albee Festival last November and decided then to bring it to <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION>. The author is best known for `` Who's Afraid of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> Woolf?'' and `` The Zoo Story,'' plays of the 1960s that are also being revived at this year's Fringe. Critic <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Affleck </PERSON>, writing in The Scotsman, called `` Man'' a remarkable play, and the same newspaper quoted <PERSON> Albee </PERSON> in a long-distance interview as saying he was ecstatic with its local reception in light of his `` long war with the drama critics of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON> said her staging was probably more `` audience-friendly'' than the strident, haranguing production so coolly received in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> _ a production she did not see. `` The original production was a little more hostile to the audience, and the critics were lying in wait for him -LRB- <PERSON> Albee </PERSON> -RRB-,'' she said. The play is structured around a lecture given by a man who mysteriously grows a third arm one day and then watches it shrink. `` What <PERSON> Albee </PERSON> does is make us question our own value system,'' said <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON>. `` I think the play is brilliant.'' Not every unsung American play has its reputation restored in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Henley </PERSON>'s `` The Wake of <PERSON> Jamey </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>,'' a short-lived Broadway entry early this decade, got mixed-to-poor reviews at this year's Fringe, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabe </PERSON>'s `` Hurlyburly,'' a Broadway success, was denounced in The Scotsman as `` exploitative, bad-mouthed, and boring.''
</TEXT>
