<HEAD>NBC's `Sister Kate' Succeeds on Surprise Casting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Not a lot of people would have seized upon this casting: <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Beacham </PERSON> of `` Dynasty'' as a <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> nun taking care of orphans. What a surprise. It works. <PERSON> Beacham </PERSON>'s Sister <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> is a no-nonsense nun who does n't particularly like people, having been transferred to the orphanage from an archeological dig where she was unearthing bones, `` my preferred way of dealing with people.'' Her new charges _ ranging from a pint-sized Rastafarian to a boy-crazy teen-ager _ have prided themselves in running off a series of kindly old priests. Of course, in Sister <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> they meet their match. `` Sister Kate'' is predictable fare, but a nice family comedy, and <PERSON> Beacham </PERSON> looks like a break-out sitcom star. The show is well-paired on Sunday night with <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` My Two Dads.''
</TEXT>
