<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Businessman Relates Escape From Drug World After 20 Years of Crime</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX10 of Aug. 31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> left prison five years ago, no one believed he was a changed man. After all, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> began smoking marijuana at age 13 and graduated to snorting cocaine and heroin at 14, feeding an appetite for drugs that for two decades dictated a life of crime. `` I knew the ins and outs of drugs,'' he says, explaining that as a youngster he had seen the debilitating effects of illicit drug use, `` but it was the slick thing to do. I wanted to belong, to do what everybody else was doing at the time.'' So at 13, he began an involvement with drugs that would last almost 20 years. Now a successful businessman who spends his free time speaking at churches and counseling inmates at the <LOCATION> Lorton </LOCATION> correctional facilities in suburban <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> says he is committed to help others change the dead-end course of their lives. `` My whole life had been filled with drugs'' and hustling, said the 45-year-old <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, whose closely cropped hair now has an even mix of gray. Occasional use of marijuana, then cocaine and heroin, became an obsession by age 15, and `` that's when the crimes increased because I had to get drugs every day,'' he said. At first, money for the drugs came from petty thefts and what he described as `` yoke robberies'' _ strong-arm robberies or holdups without weapons. Despite all of this, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> continued to attend school and to conceal his drug habit and crimes from his mother, a Christian who demanded church attendance. Most of the expensive clothes and jewelry he bought with his ill-gotten money were stored at friends' houses <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s first car at age 16 _ a 1964 Mustang that then held the same prestige as today's BMW _ was parked around corners and in friends' garages and driveways. `` Robbery was the thing in the'60s; we went from bank robbery to robbing private businesses,'' said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, whose first adult arrest came in the summer of 1966 when he joined some friends who hijacked a truck full of merchandise. The charges were later dropped. His profession as a thief ended in April 1968 when <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> was arrested for felony murder after an accomplice shot a clerk during a postal robbery. While waiting 18 months in jail to go to trial, he met two men from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> who convinced him that selling drugs would reap greater profits faster. So when charges again were dropped, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> headed for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where his friends `` introduced me to a new hustle, selling drugs.'' `` The money came so fast, there was no comparison'' with money from the robberies, said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>. `` That's part of the problem today. The money is fast. There is no money in the world faster than drug money.'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s success was meteoric. `` I was able to acquire a grocery store, a new home, an apartment building, new cars, fine clothes, jewelry and traveled around the world. I met people that put me in a position to get more and better drugs.'' But as his business skyrocketed, so did his craving for drugs. `` I went from snorting drugs to shooting drugs because I had a raw habit,'' he said. `` When you become your best customer, you become unreliable, as far as the supplier is concerned, as far as paying money back.'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s drug suppliers entrusted him with smaller and smaller amounts of drugs, dropping from 10 kilograms down to five kilos and then three. He also had frequent skirmishes with the law and was convicted four times on drug charges. `` When you know people, getting drugs or going to jail was n't a problem to me because my life pattern never had to change,'' said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, explaining that drugs were `` just as plentiful in jail as on the streets, if not more plentiful.'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, who married at age 17, said his son brought him drugs in prison, concealing them in tennis balls or using other ingenious smuggling techniques. `` My last arrest had me facing 60 years in jail,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said, but he was sentenced to only 20 months-to-five years at <LOCATION> Lorton </LOCATION>. It was during his last incarceration that <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> met several <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> inmates who persuaded him to change his life. After his release, he was still viewed skeptically by his family, especially his wife who had left him three years into the marriage. `` People did n't want to believe it. They've heard before I'd changed and then I'd come out and do the same thing,'' he said `` But the longer I stayed out the more they had to re-evaluate whether or not I was serious.'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s family began to respect his commitment. Then in April 1988, his 24-year-old son, a dealer himself, was killed on the street, shot nine times. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said he successfully suppressed his urge to retaliate against his son's murderers. Today, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> is production manager of a print shop in <LOCATION> Reston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, making $ 40,000 a year that he can spend `` without worrying about the police kicking my door in.'' After a 20-year separation, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> and his wife reunited last November and live in suburban <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 3</NOTE>
