<HEAD>The White Powder Road to the High Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When law officers arrested high school dropout <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> `` Tony <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'' <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> just a month short of his 25th birthday, they gawped openly at his $ 730,000 <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> home and fleet of luxury cars. This was no Wall Street financier or wunderkind film producer. Like many young people seeking their share of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream, <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> amassed his fortune the new-fashioned way _ he sold cocaine. His 100-employee, multimillion-dollar operation was based in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> neighborhood of <LOCATION> Laurelton </LOCATION>, the working-class section of south <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> where <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> grew up. His headquarters was the corner of <LOCATION> Merrick </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boulevard </LOCATION> and 226th Street, but he also sold drugs in <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The Mickens operation was n't the largest in drug-infested south <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>. But authorities said it was one of the most sophisticated. `` How many 25-year-olds do you know who can accumulate so much wealth and know how to launder illegal money?'' one investigator said after <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON>' arrest last year. Two months ago a <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> federal jury convicted him of 16 counts of drug conspiracy, tax evasion and money laundering. He faces sentences totaling 220 years of prison time. Defense lawyer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Simels </PERSON> maintains his client's innocence. He argues that the fabulous wealth was left by <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON>' late father, said to be a big-time Queens numbers runner. But <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney for the Eastern District of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> personally cleared at least $ 2.5 million in cocaine profits in the 3 -LCB- years before his arrest. Like other young drug kingpins, <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> spent it freely and lavishly, <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON> said. In <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON>' circle, incredible sums of money changed hands, packed in bags and shoeboxes. With sacks of cash and stacks of money orders, <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> bought a $ 100,000 custom <ORGANIZATION> Rolls-Royce </ORGANIZATION> equipped with a pair of television sets, VCRs and videogames. He maintained a fleet of sporty, expensive cars _ BMWs, Porsches, <ORGANIZATION> Ferraris </ORGANIZATION> and Mercedes-Benzes _ in which the popular young man took neighborhood kids for rides. `` He was the big talk of <LOCATION> Laurelton </LOCATION>,'' said a teen-age neighborhood girl, who declined to give her name. `` They'd talk about his cars, and how ` fly' they were, how nice.'' <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> took his moniker from <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Montana </PERSON>, the violent, high-living cocaine-addicted gangster portrayed by actor <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Pacino </PERSON> in `` Scarface,'' prosecutors said. `` He tried to model his existence after that character,'' said Capt. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattes </PERSON> of the Queens narcotics squad. His fascination with the movie was complete: he named his businesses after <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Montana </PERSON>, and several copies of `` Scarface'' were found in <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON>' home and in his limousine. Agents who arrested <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> at his home in exclusive <LOCATION> Dix </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> were amazed to find a Jacuzzi for 10 and a spiral staircase that ended at a fully outfitted workout gym. He wore fancy clothes and gold jewelry and owned homes in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, where he docked his 38-foot-long yacht. `` That someone so young could become a multimillionaire by selling cocaine shows how tempting and lucrative the business is,'' said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pileggi </PERSON>. Prosecutors said <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> showed financial savvy in making his purchases and hiding his income. Much of his property was registered under false names or by his girlfriend, <PERSON> Shelby </PERSON> <PERSON> Kearney </PERSON>, who was convicted of helping him launder money. Major purchases were made in installments under $ 10,000 to avoid federal financial reporting requirements. Unlike most drug dealers, <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON>' empire went beyond the cocaine trade: He owned several stores, the <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lounge </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Montana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cleaners </ORGANIZATION>, all of which _ along with the houses, boat and cars _ were seized by the government. <ORGANIZATION> Montana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Goods </ORGANIZATION>, one of those companies, sponsored a team in a summer basketball league in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Albans </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> also coached the team; among the players was <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, guard for the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Knicks </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> `` enjoyed a good reputation for truthfulness and honesty,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said in testimony at <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON>' trial. Others also defended him. An old friend told <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newsday </ORGANIZATION> that wealth notwithstanding, <PERSON> Mickens </PERSON> had not changed very much. He was still `` one of the guys, not <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> the drug dealer, just cool <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> the guy we grew up with.''
