<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No one can accuse <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Bochco </PERSON> of resorting to stale, old formulas with `` <PERSON> Doogie </PERSON> <PERSON> Howser </PERSON>, M.D.'' In the pilot, our hero interrupts his driving test to administer emergency medical aid at the scene of a traffic accident. So why is a doctor just now getting his driver's license? He's only 16. The half-hour `` dramedy'' is the first show to derive from <PERSON> Bochco </PERSON>'s multimillion-dollar development deal with <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. `` Howser'' is a well-made show but it remains to be seen what audience will take to an offbeat pairing of adult and teen themes. In the pilot, <PERSON> Doogie </PERSON> wins his first kiss and loses his first patient. The series is slotted in a decidedly adult time period, replacing <PERSON> Bochco </PERSON>'s other dramedy, `` Hooperman,'' on Wednesday. <PERSON> Bochco </PERSON> says it is feasible that a child genius, who graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> at 10, could have a medical license at 16. The premise interested him because his late father was a violin prodigy. <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> is an excellent actor, and taking the same character in and out of parallel lives is kind of interesting, dramatically. But do we want to watch <PERSON> Doogie </PERSON> make life-and-death decisions at the hospital, then come home and sulk because his father -LRB- <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sikking </PERSON> -RRB- wo n't loan him the car? <PERSON> Bochco </PERSON> has tried to do something different here, but it has ended up just being kind of weird.
