<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sun Sept. 3 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Declaring Drug War is Easy, Fighting One is Not</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With no secret weapons available, the strategy President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> sets Tuesday night for the war on drugs will foretell a long struggle in the trenches. That is going to demand patience, persistence and drudgery, long after the drama of a nationally televised re-declaration of war has faded. The government has declared war on drugs before. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has commanded such an effort before. And the government has reported some progress, but against a changing and growing target. Now, as president, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is setting a course to redeem a campaign pledge underscored in his inaugural address: `` Take my word for it: this scourge will stop.'' As <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> outlines his drug-fighting program in an address to the nation, Americans are said to be ready to make war on drugs whatever the cost, even if it takes a tax increase. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said it wo n't, that the needed funds will be shifted from other programs. `` In key ways today, the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are in a wartime mode and sense a national emergency in the drug crisis,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallup </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, reporting on an early summer poll his organization conducted for the drug-fighting effort. That sense of crisis has since been heightened by the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> government crackdown on the drug lords blamed for the murder of a presidential candidate there, and said to be responsible for about 80 percent of the cocaine flowing into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> already is sending $ 65 million worth of arms and equipment to help the Colombians combat the drug cartels. The broader administration program will propose up to $ 260 million in economic and military drug-fighting aid to <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is presenting a strategy report required by the law that set up the Office of National Drug Control Policy, the new agency <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> heads. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> could have left the report to his drug czar; by delivering it himself, in his first nationally televised address from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the president puts the drug crisis at the top of his autumn agenda. There's likely to be more drama in the medium than in the message. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> has said again and again that there is no magic bullet to be fired in the drug battle. His report sets goals far more cautious than the rhetoric of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign or inaugural address _ a 10 percent reduction in drug use in the next two years; 50 percent in 10 years. The tools include increased federal aid to local law enforcement agencies; more prisons to house drug offenders; tougher and more certain punishment; more funds for drug education and treatment; interdiction efforts that will increase the role of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military. During the 1988 campaign, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> advocated execution of big-time drug dealers. `` For those who commit drug-related murders, for the drug kingpins who are poisoning our kids, the penalty should be death,'' he said. `` If this is war then let's treat it as such. Let's get these killers off the streets.'' That proposal has not been mentioned in advance discussion of the drug strategy report. All told, the administration plan would cost an estimated $ 8 billion, about $ 2 billion over the current budget for the programs involved. There will be debate on whether that's enough, how much should be spent, and how it should be used. Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and a prime sponsor of the bill that created the new drug policy agency, has complained that the government so far has n't been willing to pay what's needed to fight the drug epidemic `` We have no war on drugs,'' he told a mid-August conference of corrections officers. `` We need a D-Day, we do n't need another <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, who is to deliver a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> response to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> after the president speaks Tuesday night, proposed this week that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> set up a system of debt relief for Latin nations that subsidize shifts away from the coca crops that are the raw material of cocaine. The Gallup survey, conducted in June and July and donated to the drug agency, reflected a D-Day mood. The poll of 1,005 adults and 500 teen-agers showed that Americans consider drugs to be the most serious problem facing the nation, with no other single concern even coming close. Gallup said the survey showed a public willingness to sacrifice as in wartime, with a majority favoring increased spending to combat drugs and willing to pay higher taxes if necessary. By all those measures, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> address comes at prime time on the calendar as well as the clock, to a nation fed up with the drug crisis and ready for action. That bodes well for the send-off. The greater challenge may come in finding the staying power for a drug war that wo n't end any time soon.
</TEXT>
