<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--VirginStand Adv04   08-31 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Virgin Stand, Adv 04,0802</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Sept. 4, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Spared By Man, Virgin Stand of Spruce Is Battered By Nature</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURG, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The hulking roots of a toppled tree, covered by lush moss and surrounded by saplings, symbolize the extremes of life and death in one of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s last virgin stands of spruce and balsam fir. The 110-acre stand, on the <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> headwaters six miles from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, has faced threats from nature as well as man in the past century. What is left, owned by The Nature Conservancy, is in many places not a pretty sight. Saved by man from logging operations but ravaged by the great hurricane of 1938 and a spruce budworm attack in the early 1970s, the towering spruce trees, some estimated to be 350 years old, are few and far between. `` It looks sad up there now after the budworm. It was so pretty up there before,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON>, a paper company forester instrumental in saving the stand situated at <LOCATION> Norton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pool </LOCATION> <LOCATION> on </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inlet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>. The boggy lowlands are not ideal for spruce and fir, and more impressive specimens can be found elsewhere, said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> John </PERSON>. But at <ORGANIZATION> Norton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pool </ORGANIZATION>, he said, `` the idea is that they have n't been trashed. `` You can see what nature does to itself, too. ... It killed its own trees, and there's thick regeneration coming up underneath.'' The stand's inaccessibility _ it's 50 miles north of the state's last stoplight _ has helped protect it through the ages It faced its first threat in recorded times, from lumbering, in the late 1800s. The <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lumber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> bought it as part of 125,000 acres of timberland in 1888, and reached East Inlet 10 years later. The 10,000-acre East Inlet watershed had never been cut, but its spruce was in demand. The spring of 1898 was extremely dry, however, and the loggers were unable to float logs down to mills and railroads. After a few weeks, they gave up. There was a budworm onslaught from about 1910 to 1915, though it was n't nearly as serious as the infestation in the 1970s. The tiny worms, which later become moths, eat spruce and fir needles, sometimes killing the trees. Nature again wrought havoc in the hurricane of September 1938. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON> estimated that at least 25 percent of the spruce and even more of the fir were blown down or broken. <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON> observed the destruction for the first time in 1941 when, at age 23, he was in the first <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> team surveying to mark trees for cutting. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Regis </PERSON> had bought <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lumber </ORGANIZATION> in 1926. `` Sometimes we seemed to go a quarter of a mile climbing on top of blown-down trees. ... You'd be perhaps 10, 15, 20 feet in the air, climbing over that stuff.'' The team recognized that the trees still standing were special, he said. `` Most of us had n't been in large old-growth stands before.'' <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Regis </PERSON> began cutting in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inlet </LOCATION> in the late 1940s, though not in the area later protected. By the 1950s, with pressure increasing to cut the huge trees, <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON> and some colleagues began plotting actively to spare it. `` Some of us kind of decided, ` Gee, you know, let's kind of skip around that. We can always get back get to it. That's what we had to tell some of the other people in the company who said, ` Why did you bypass that?''' The <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and other conservation groups began expressing interest in saving the area that also held rare birds and plants. In the late 1960s, <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Regis </PERSON> agreed to save the stand, but <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Champion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which took it over in 1984, for years declined to give the stand to the groups, saying the company was taking care of it. Champion eventually deeded the land to The Nature Conservancy in July 1987. By then, nature had wreaked havoc. In 1974, masses of budworms swept into the region in a five-year infestation. `` Lots of places, very close to 100 percent of the fir got picked off, and a lot of the other growth, the small trees underneath,'' <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON> said. `` The spruce was a little bit more resistant to it, but it got hit badly up there. It really spoiled the looks of it.'' But <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON> remains philosophical about <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> <PERSON> Pool </PERSON>'s future. `` In this part of the world, things are both man and nature, and unless they pave it over, nature recovers,'' he said. `` Another 100 years or so and it'll look good again.''
</TEXT>
