<HEAD>Construction Contracts Up In July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A rebound in public works projects helped push the level of new construction contracts nationwide up by 2 percent during July, a survey found. The survey, by the F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, found that overall construction last month rose to an annual rate of $ 256.6 billion, a three-month high, <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. That followed a 2 percent drop in June. Contracts for public works and utilities construction jumped 5 percent in July to an annual rate of $ 45.7 billion. July contracts for new non-residential buildings, mainly commercial, industrial and institutional structures, rose 2 percent to $ 91.8 billion. But residential home contracts were up a modest 1 percent, with multifamily houses and hotels declining slightly and single-family homes advancing 2 percent. `` It's still early to be looking for a surge of one family housing in response to falling mortgage rates, as July's data bear out,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> group's vice president and chief economist. `` In another month or two, when inventory of unsold new homes is worked down and recession fears subside, conditions will be right for a solid recovery of homebuilding.'' For the first seven months of this year the unadjusted total of all newly started construction was $ 149.8 billion, off 1 percent from the same period a year ago.
