<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Stellar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and Japanese-backed rival <ORGANIZATION> Ardent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, money-losing makers of high-powered graphics computers, announced they have agreed to merge to form a company named <ORGANIZATION> Stardent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kubota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns 44 percent of Ardent, will own 22 percent of the combined companies and eventually will take over all manufacturing as well as <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> distribution of the consolidated product line, the companies said Wednesday The privately owned companies make single-user computers that sell for close to $ 100,000 and are used by scientists and engineers for complex jobs such as modeling the way air flows over turbine blades in a jet engine. Both <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>, Mass.-based Stellar and <LOCATION> Sunnyvale </LOCATION>, Calif.-based Ardent were founded in late 1985, started shipping machines about a year ago and have not yet reached profitability. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Poduska </PERSON>, Stellar's founder and chairman, predicted the combined company would attain profitability by the end of 1990 and reach revenue of at least $ 100 million, twice what the two companies will gross this year. <PERSON> Poduska </PERSON> will serve as co-chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Stardent </ORGANIZATION> with <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michels </PERSON>, Ardent's chairman and chief executive. Eventually the companies plan to select a single chief executive and headquarters. The companies will merge their product lines by early 1991. <PERSON> Poduska </PERSON> said software written for the old machines would run on the new ones with a minimum of reworking. In addition, he said, the new company will broaden its product line to range from machines costing $ 15,000 or $ 20,000 to ones costing $ 200,000. The combination is a straight merger, so no money is changing hands. `` We have a marriage of two equals that is really something to watch out for,'' <PERSON> Poduska </PERSON> said in an interview. Word of the planned merger circulated on Tuesday. The deal is subject to a definitive agreement and requires the approval of shareholders and the government.
