<HEAD>Concerns Over Indoor Pollution Create Work For Toxin Cleaners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Robson </PERSON> says more than one person has compared his business to the Ghostbusters of movie fame. He has a team, armed with chemicals, that goes into offices to fight invisible enemies. The enemies in this case are the indoor pollutants that environmental officials say are threatening workers' health. Increased awareness of indoor pollution, which some say is as dangerous as the toxins floating around outdoors, is creating plenty of work for companies such as <PERSON> Robson </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> BriteTech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` Five or seven years ago it was hard to go in and convince someone they had indoor pollution,'' said <PERSON> Robson </PERSON>, president and founder of <ORGANIZATION> BriteTech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Norcross </ORGANIZATION>, which franchises its services. `` They'd look around and say, ` I do n't see it.''' An <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> survey conducted last year found that 1,200 companies were providing indoor environmental cleaning or analysis work, most of it for radon or asbestos. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Axelrad </PERSON>, director of the indoor air division of the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and Radiation in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said many of these companies are expanding into the field of indoor air pollution, though the survey did not give a precise figure `` Our sense is it is a growing business,'' <PERSON> Axelrad </PERSON> said. `` A lot of -LRB- those doing -RRB- industrial hygiene work are finding pretty good demand for their services,'' he said. `` We definitely think this is an emerging issue,'' <PERSON> Axelrad </PERSON> said of indoor pollution. An <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> report released last spring said pesticides, radon, asbestos, tobacco smoke, bacteria and mold inhaled in poorly ventilated offices may threaten the health of Americans as much as outdoor pollution. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> report attributed more than $ 1 billion in medical costs from cancer and heart disease to eight indoor pollutants. The combination of indoor pollutants has earned the name `` Sick Building Syndrome.'' Americans spend most of their time indoors, and <PERSON> Robson </PERSON> said that as more people become aware of the syndrome they want something done about it. People often are surprised by the pollution found in an office or other indoor environment, <PERSON> Robson </PERSON> said. The toxins in cigarette smoke, for example, stick to walls and ceilings and stay there for years, he said. `` There are 350 types of gases and pollutants in tobacco smoke,'' he said. `` If the building was contaminated before, the residue is still there.'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Almond </PERSON>, staff engineer at <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Baptist </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, a customer of a BriteTech franchisee, said hospitals are extremely concerned with indoor pollution. But he said that only in recent years has the means for fighting the toxins grown more sophisticated. `` We were very much concerned with odors. We ca n't have any because of our critical-care areas,'' Almond said. `` We used to have a can of Lysol, and that's what we used.'' Almond said the availability of indoor pollution-control companies is contributing to cleaner hospitals. With the growth of an industry that deals with something that often can not be seen, however, comes inevitable fraud, officials warn. <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said the agency conducts training programs for both pollution testers and `` mitigators'' and makes lists of participants available to its regional offices in an effort to minimize fraud. `` We know there are some con artists out there who come in with the mayonnaise jar, scoop up some air and then tell them -LRB- customers -RRB- they'll analyze it and get back to them,'' Ms. <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. BriteTech uses a variety of measuring tools and also talks to building occupants to determine the level of pollution. The company also suggests remedies and has about 20 formulas _ all non-toxic and biodegradable, <PERSON> Robson </PERSON> said _ for cleaning indoor areas. <PERSON> Robson </PERSON> said the cleaning process involves spraying a chemical mist onto surfaces, which dissolves the toxins. There is no scrubbing, he said. The cleaning materials also are sprayed into ventilation systems, though in extreme cases installation of a new air conditioning system may be recommended. Though the cost of BriteTech service varies according to the type of surface and degree of pollution, <PERSON> Robson </PERSON> said franchises generally charge 25 cents to 50 cents per square foot. BriteTech is a relatively new player in the indoor pollution field, having started in January. <PERSON> Robson </PERSON> said he believes BriteTech is the first franchisor in the industry. The company has 12 franchises operating in nine states. Franchisees must put up a fee of $ 15,000 to $ 25,000 plus $ 10,000 working capital. The Norcross headquarters provides training, materials and a full-time staff including a chemist. <PERSON> Robson </PERSON> said his company's revenues so far are about $ 3 million a year, and he is hoping for 45 units and revenues of $ 20 million by the middle of next year.
</TEXT>
