<HEAD>Supreme Court Sets JOA Arguments Oct. 30</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> says it will hear arguments in two months on whether The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> should be allowed to merge some operations to cut costs. The court said Wednesday it will hear an hour of arguments at 2 p.m. Oct. 30. The Free Press, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and the News, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, have sought since May 1986 to merge business operations such as advertising, production and circulation to cut costs, while keeping news and editorial operations separate The newspapers said the Free Press will fail if the joint operating agreement is n't granted under the federal Newspaper Preservation Act. Former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> approved the limited antitrust exemption Aug. 8, 1988. But <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens for an <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> is challenging <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s ruling, contending the newspapers have failed to prove the Free Press is in danger of failing, and saying a <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> would give the nation's two largest newspaper chains unfair control of the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> market.
