<HEAD>Deere Announces New Chief Executive Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOLINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Deere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> has given up his title as chief executive officer after directing <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> through its darkest days and into an era of record profits <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, 64, relinquished the company's reins Wednesday to <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Becherer </PERSON>, currently president of <PERSON> Deere </PERSON>, the world leader in tractor and agricultural-implement manufacturing. `` The action ... is reflective of the commitment by <ORGANIZATION> Deere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors to an orderly and effective management succession plan,'' <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said in a news release `` This new appointment indicates the board's confidence in his ability to continue to exercise the kind of effective leadership that will help ensure <ORGANIZATION> Deere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s progress in the years ahead,'' said <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, who retains his title as chairman. <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Combs </PERSON> said no firm date has been established for <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>'s retirement, although company policy mandates he step down in 15 months on his 66th birthday in December 1990. `` Mr. <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> will remain very active in leading the company up until his retirement,'' <PERSON> Combs </PERSON> said. The choice of <PERSON> Becherer </PERSON> as heir-apparent signals the end of a remarkable near 40-year tenure which saw <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> take control in 1982 as the company stood on the brink of collapse. Deere accumulated $ 328 million in losses in two years, and its operating losses totaled $ 637 million in the six-year period 1982-87. <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> orchestrated a brutal cost-cutting program and laided off about 12,000 workers as the farm crisis gripped the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and caused thousands of farm foreclosures nationwide. The problems were compounded by a 163-day work stoppage at 13 Deere plants in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and four other states that ended Feb. 1, 1987, when workers accepted a wage freeze. Since then, <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> has led the 152-year-old company to its highest profit levels ever. Aided by a diversification plan that saw <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> enter insurance, consumer credit, mail-order catalogue and health maintenance fields, the company has flourished. In 1988, <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> earned $ 315.4 million on sales of $ 5.3 billion despite a crippling drought that cut corn and soybean yields in half in key states like <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. Profits and sales again are on a record pace nine months into the 1989 fiscal year. <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, an East Moline native, was the first person not a member of the <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> family by blood or marriage to run the company. But he's the ultimate company man. Raised a few miles from the corporate headquarters, <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>'s father was a middle-level manager at a Deere foundry <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> joined <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> in 1950 and rose through the ranks until attaining a seat on the board of directors in 1974. He was named president in 1978 and achieved the post of chief operating officer in 1979. <PERSON> Becherer </PERSON>, 54, joined <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> in 1962 and followed a course to the top similar to <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>'s in marketing and extensive overseas work. He joined the board of directors in 1986 and was elected president and chief operating officer in 1987.
