<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Trade     08-31 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Trade,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Economists Criticize U.S. Result-Oriented Trade Approach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of Japanese economists said Thursday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could expect only greater frictions with its trading partners if it adopted an advisory committee's calls for a more `` result-oriented'' approach to lowering the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. The economists also said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> must re-examine such business practices as the tendency of Japanese doing business mainly with each other, manufacturers' dominance in price-setting, and discriminatory treatment against imported products. But while these practices may be frustrating to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> exporters, they have little to do with the large trade imbalances of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Masaru </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoshitomi </PERSON>, director-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> and a leading member of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan-U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The council presented a counterproposal Thursday to recommendations in February by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON>' Advisory Committee for Trade Policy and Negotiation. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> panel, headed by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, recommended that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative take a more result-oriented approach to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. This would mean judging Japanese actions by how much they reduce the deficit. <ORGANIZATION> Yoshitomi </ORGANIZATION>'s group recommends handling trade imbalance issues separately from trade policy issues, saying that lowering barriers is a separate issue from achieving a balance between imports and exports. It argues that `` it is totally wrong'' to see a large deficit as reflecting a country's free trade practices and a large surplus as reflecting trade restrictions. `` Fundamental confusion is often seen in many journalistic articles,'' it says. Referring to growing protectionist sentiment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> against Japanese trade practices, the report says the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should not be frustrated by the lack of progress in reducing trade deficits and should not let politicians use the sentiment politically. The report also attacks the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' use against <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> of new trade legislation providing for retaliation if the two sides can not negotiate a solution to Japanese trade practices the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> deems unfair. `` The global free trade system would completely break down if every country adopted the same policies based on unilateral judgments of unfair trade practices of trading partners in specific products, especially when no country always acts fairly, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' it says. <ORGANIZATION> Yoshitomi </ORGANIZATION> stressed that <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> must change in order to reduce their trade deficit, rather than simply demanding that its trade partners change. `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> technological hegemony was established through essentially a mass production system since early this century,'' he said. But the situation may have changed in favor of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, so that many aspects of the American system must adapt, he said.
</TEXT>
