<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 1333EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv01   08-31 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 01,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Friday, Sept. 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Deficit That Would Not Die</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It may not make your day to hear this, but the federal budget deficit will soon be back making news. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> returns to session after Labor Day facing a deadline just a few weeks away to shrink, somehow, the projected gap between income and outgo for the government fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. If it does n't succeed, then the law known as Gramm-Rudman-Hollings calls for automatic cuts in spending to bring the deficit down within specified limits. `` The stage is set for intense negotiations over the budget in the coming weeks,'' says <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, political analyst for the investment firm of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Unless something is done, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget staff says, the government will stand to run $ 116 billion, give or take a few hundred million, in the red for fiscal 1990. That's $ 16 billion more than mandated by Gramm-Rudman-Hollings, but a conservative estimate by comparison to others, who have projected deficits as large as $ 140 billion. It seems safe to assume that this will bring a lot of the usual scenes that have become so familiar in the 1980s _ wrangling between the administration and the lawmakers, late-night maneuvering and some sort of last-minute compromise that will keep the government lurching along. Lots of people will pay no attention, and why should they? The debate over the deficit has been going on since the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administration at least, and the situation never seems to change much. Besides, whatever is done this fall, the underlying problem wo n't go away `` Any budget pain encountered in getting under the Gramm-Rudman ceiling for 1990 will be dwarfed by the ` agony' coming down the track for 1991,'' observes the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Babson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Report </ORGANIZATION>, a Boston-based newsletter. In that fiscal year, <ORGANIZATION> Gramm-Rudman </ORGANIZATION> calls for a deficit limit of $ 64 billion. Some people trace the origins of the much-bewailed `` breakdown of the budget process'' to the mid-1960s, when the nation was faced with a choice of how to spend its large, but still finite, resources. Should it build up its expensive role in the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> war, or should it embark on a sweeping campaign to deal with domestic problems? Guns AND butter, decided President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. The deficit widened with the recessions and oil crises of the 1970s, and got still worse during the `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> revolution'' of the'80s. Along the way, Americans have taken part in a long experiment determining what happens to their economy in a period of chronic deficits. It turns out that policy measures taken in response to a deficit can cause severe economic slumps, runaway booms, or long periods of mere muddling through. They can foster rising inflation or declining inflation, higher interest rates or lower interest rates. In short, under the deficits of the past two decades, the nation has witnessed just about every conceivable economic environment _ except for the kind of calamity so many analysts of the problem have predicted. Logic still dictates that the government can not go on indefinitely spending more than it takes in. Experience has shown that it could in fact do just that for longer than many experts thought possible. Blamed for everything from the stock market of crash of 1987 to a decline in family values, the deficit persists. Having survived this far, it seems ready to take on the 1990s with plenty of energy left.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday Sept. 1</NOTE>
