<HEAD>Volkswagen Stops Shipping Through Albany Port</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has moved its Northeast distribution center from the Port of <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the second major shipper the <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> port has lost in two months, officials said. <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it was transferring its shipping center to the port of <LOCATION> Davisville </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, effective immediately. The West German automaker had shipped more than 100,000 cars up the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> in the last three years. The pullout will mean work reductions for up to 175 longshoremen, while about a dozen jobs will be lost in related businesses, officials said. <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> shipped about 20,500 cars to <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> last year, accounting for $ 135,000 in revenues, about 9 percent of the port's receipts The move comes after <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which shipped bananas from <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> for 17 years, moved its shipments to <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del. </LOCATION>, this summer. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> had been the port's biggest clients, accounting for 80 percent of longshoremen's work, union officials said. <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> was `` the last major, steady client for us, said <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Turnwall </PERSON>, port manager for <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Terminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operators </ORGANIZATION>, which manages the port. <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> decided to leave <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> after 11 years despite incentives offered by the port and union leaders, the <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> reported. Those incentives included freezing dock fees in 1990, the newspaper reported. `` It's simply more economical to import through <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> than to <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> told the newspaper. Shipping sources said <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION>, facing slumping <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales, had complained about the costs of doing business at the <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> port. The <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> port at an old <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> base near <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION> is about 10 miles from the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> is about 140 miles from the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>.
