 Sir <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>, one of the three financiers leading the hostile takeover bid for <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday a British regulatory panel must extend its deadline or his takeover attempt will fail. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Panel on Takeovers and Mergers requires that all conditions of a bid, including <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> regulatory hurdles, must be completed within 81 days of the posting of the bidder's formal offer document. `` If there is no extension from the panel it's very hard to see the offer succeeding,'' <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>'s consortium, <ORGANIZATION> Hoylake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, posted its 13.4 billion pound, or $ 21.4 billion, bid for BAT and its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiaries on Aug. 8, which leaves the group 58 days to meet <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> regulatory requirements. London-based BAT, the world's largest tobacco company, has significant interests in financial services, paper and retailing _ including such <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> holdings as the <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Field </ORGANIZATION> department stores and <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> on Thursday also launched an attack on regulatory commissions in several <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> states `` for obstructing the bid.'' `` The -LRB- state -RRB- regulators have got to ask themselves whether they are going to be a poison pill or are going to allow free trade,'' he said. <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> is joined by British banker <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothschild </PERSON> and Australian investor <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> in leading the BAT takeover bid, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s largest to date. The British takeover panel said a decision on the extension request would be made in the next few weeks. BAT shares were down 14 pence, or around 22 cents, at 823 pence, or $ 13.10, a share on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> following <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>'s remarks. <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> is offering 878 pence, or $ 14.10, a share for BAT.
