<FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 2211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Coffee-Changes Adv03   08-31 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Coffee-Changes, Adv 03,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Sept. 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Coffee Tasters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Americans Change Taste, Consume Less Coffee, Turn To Gourmet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ever since the coffee bean's muddy broth was first served 1,000 years ago, it's survived religious persecution, official banishment and suspected links to maladies ranging from heart attacks to male impotence. It's been written about, used for inspiration and put to music. <PERSON> Johann </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebastian </PERSON> <PERSON> Bach </PERSON> composed `` Coffee Cantata,'' which parodied those who sought to suppress the brew. French philosopher <PERSON> Voltaire </PERSON> reportedly drank 50 cups a day. Coffee as a drink first appeared in the year 900 in a part of Arabia that is now <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION>. It became so popular in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> that Moslem priests complained the drink emptied the mosques. Coffee's rapid spread to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> led devout <PERSON> Catholics </PERSON> to denounce it as an infidel's brew. <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> the Great of <LOCATION> Prussia </LOCATION> once banned coffee because he thought it threatened consumption of beer, the national drink. A study of coffee by Find-SVP, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> research concern, said coffee's success in 16th century <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> led women to agitate for a prohibition, claiming the drink inhibited the virility of their mates. In more modern times, medical studies have concluded the stimulant caffeine in coffee may contribute to higher cholesterol levels and heart disease. Health concerns about coffee is one reason it's popularity among Americans is diminishing, according to recent studies which show a long-term decline in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumption. While three out of four Americans regularly downed at least a cup a day in 1962, only half of the population reported drinking coffee last year, a study by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> shows. In 1988, the average number of cups of coffee consumed per person per day was 1.67 cups, down from 1.76 cups in 1987 and 46 percent below 1962 when per capita consumption was 3.12 cups, the <ORGANIZATION> ICO </ORGANIZATION> study found. Even hard core drinkers drink less _ 3.34 cups per day in 1988 compared with 4.17 cups in 1962. That does n't mean coffee drinking is doomed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which remains the largest market for coffee. Although Americans constitute only 5 percent of the world population, they still drink a third of the planet's coffee, about 360 million cups a day, a report by the <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> shows. Americans have also become more selective about their brew. Consumption of instant coffee has dipped appreciably in the last three decades. Though the number of people drinking decaffeinated coffee last year was four times that of 1962, the amount consumed declined, from 17.5 percent in 1987 to 15.8 percent in 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> ICO </ORGANIZATION> study found. The most noticeable change has been in the habits of those 20-29 years of age whose per capita consumption fell from about 3 -LCB- cups a day in 1962 to less than one cup in 1988. People older than 30, who consumed more than 4 cups in 1962, now drink about two cups a day. Analysts also attribute the decline in coffee drinking to the rise in popularity of soft drinks, which has increased proportionally. Since 1985, soft drinks have overtaken coffee as the most consumed beverage. But consumer concern about natural, healthy foods also has led to a rise in the popularity of gourmet coffees. Despite the decline in overall coffee consumption, sales of gourmet blends have grown about 25 percent a year since 1975, says the Find-SVP study. Specialty whole bean and gourmet coffee now constitutes 8 percent of the total coffee market, says <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> DeChillo </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. DeChillo defines gourmet coffee as high quality, flavored or unflavored coffee. The trend to increased supermarket distribution is the most significant development in the industry and in helping popularize gourmet coffee. It has also grown in restaurants. With the two biggest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> roasters _ <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ getting into the act and expanding their marketing of gourmet coffees at supermarkets, sales of gourmet coffee, which totaled about $ 600 million in 1988, are forecast to double in another decade, the Find-SVP study says. Of the gourmet segment, flavored coffees are the fastest growing segment and the most controversial. Many purists shun flavored coffees because they consider them adulterated. But it is this segment that has captured younger consumers, who have grown up on soft drinks and sweeter-oriented taste buds, the Find-SVP study concludes. The research firm found that vanilla nut, Irish cream and chocolate are consumers' favorite flavors. Other favorites include cinnamon, chocolate raspberry and coconut.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday Sept. 3</NOTE>
