<HEAD>ZZZZ Best Insider Must Pay $900,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former <ORGANIZATION> ZZZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> official was ordered to repay $ 224,861 in illegal profits and interest from the fraudulent rug-shampooing company and to pay triple damages of $ 674,582. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Polevoi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Woodland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, a former <ORGANIZATION> ZZZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> vice president, is serving an 18-month prison sentence after pleading guilty in June to four counts of stock and tax fraud and other violations. The order for <PERSON> Polevoi </PERSON> to pay the nearly $ 900,000 came Wednesday from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelleher </PERSON>. It was based on findings that in mid-1987 <PERSON> Polevoi </PERSON> and his twin brother <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> ordered 54,200 shares of ZZZZ Best to be sold short. <PERSON> Polevoi </PERSON> knew at the time that ZZZZ Best's founder and chairman, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, was considering resigning from the <LOCATION> Reseda </LOCATION>, Calif.-based company, which was crumbling. When investors sell stock short, they seek to profit from a decline in the stock price by selling borrowed shares and buying them back later. <ORGANIZATION> ZZZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> shares fell from more than $ 5 each at the time the short sales were made to 75 cents when <PERSON> Polevoi </PERSON> completed the transactions. <PERSON> Polevoi </PERSON> and others also laundered $ 712,000 in ZZZZ Best corporate funds and bank loans through <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> casinos in the days before the company collapsed. <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON>, who convinced Wall Street and the public that he was a teen-age business genius, was convicted of 57 counts of fraud, conspiracy and other violations after investigators discovered that much of the work supposedly done by <ORGANIZATION> ZZZZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> existed only on paper. <PERSON> Minkow </PERSON> is serving a 25-year prison term and has been ordered to repay $ 26 million in illegal profits and restitution.
</TEXT>
