<FIRST>u f AM-Saab     08-31 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saab,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saab-Scania In Crisis But Refuses Clarify on Ford Bid Rumors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK SODERLUND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Swedish automaker <ORGANIZATION> Saab-Scania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AB </ORGANIZATION>, facing mounting losses and lay-offs, refused Thursday to confirm or deny news reports that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> is a leading suitor for its ailing passenger car division. Following a board meeting Thursday, <PERSON> Jan-Erik </PERSON> <PERSON> Larsson </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION>'s auto division, declined to clarify a report in the <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION> tabloid <ORGANIZATION> Expressen </ORGANIZATION> that a takeover deal with <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> was imminent. It has been rumored for several months that <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> is seeking a buyer to help salvage its crisis-ridden passenger car division and to enable it to develop a successor to its stock 900 model by 1992. The 900 model, in recent years has run into hard times on the vital <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. When it was developed, <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> managed to halve the costs by collaborating with Italian auto giant Fiat-Lancia. This time <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> reportedly first turned to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>' e <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION>, which is one-fourth-owned by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, and then turned to <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> itself. According to the Expressen report, top-level negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> are nearing their conclusion. The paper reported that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, the second-largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automaker after <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, demanded a majority share of <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION>, but other sources said the Swedish company is only willing to relinquish 20 percent to 40 percent of its stock. <PERSON> Lin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cummins </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman in <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, said, `` We can neither confirm nor deny the report.'' <PERSON> Larsson </PERSON> in a television interview Thursday night said <ORGANIZATION> Saab-Scania </ORGANIZATION> `` will remain a Swedish automaking company,'' indicating a possible refusal of a full take-over bid. <ORGANIZATION> SAAB </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Georg </PERSON> <PERSON> Karnsund </PERSON>, who refused all comment Thursday, earlier had said `` we will seek to make it on our own.'' From <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s viewpoint a take-over of <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION>'s profit-making truck division could be a golden egg. <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s top automaker <ORGANIZATION> Volvo </ORGANIZATION> two years ago purchased <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>' heavy truck division. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sells hardly any heavy trucks in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Scania </ORGANIZATION> truck division markets 75 percent of its products, which are partly produced in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Saab-Scania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AB </ORGANIZATION> last year showed a record group profit of 3.2 billion kronor, about $ 484 million at current exchange rates, up 16 percent despite increasing losses in the passenger car division. In addition to automotive and engine manufacturing, <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> makes aircraft, weapons systems and electronic equipment. <PERSON> Larsson </PERSON> on Thursday refused to confirm that the passenger car losses would mount to about one billion kronor for the first six months of this year and hit two billion kronor for the full year. However, he said losses would increase during the year from the 450 million kronor suffered in the first four months, which would virtually halve <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION>'s profit for fiscal 1989. <PERSON> Larsson </PERSON> also said a tough crisis program, including a staff reduction of about 2,000 employees, will not take effect until 1991 and admitted that the automaker is in for a couple of tough years before it can hope to break even. According to Swedish business sources, the liquidity problem of the <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> passenger car division, reportedly losing about $ 2,500 on each car it produces due to high costs and setbacks on the dollar market, is so severe it had to borrow from the parent company to cover this months' wages.
