<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-BigBanks Bjt   08-31 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Big Banks, Bjt,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Banks, Biggest in the World, Are Getting Bigger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese banks, Goliaths of international finance, are growing even bigger, leaving their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> counterparts in the dust as they keep an eye on deregulation. The 10 largest banks in the world in terms of assets are all Japanese, led by <ORGANIZATION> Daichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kangyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which has assets of $ 377 billion. That's more than <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ the two biggest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks _ combined. On Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Taiyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kobe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said they would merge in April, forming the world's second-largest bank with assets of $ 348 billion. In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, four of the top 10 banks are Japanese-owned. Deregulation starting in 1991 will allow them to expand across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, backed by the strength of their huge parent companies. A look at the unwieldy names of Japanese banks shows how they got so big: The <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taiyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kobe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> will combine the oldest bank in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> with the results of a 1973 merger of <ORGANIZATION> Taiyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Kobe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Daichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kangyo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bank </PERSON> is the result of a 1971 merger of its namesakes. And had <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> achieved its original three-way merger ambitions, the economic newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Nihon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Keizai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> says, there would have been a <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taiyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kobe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. Mergers of this scale are virtually unthinkable in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where anti-trust regulations prevent the creation of firms judged large enough to restrict competition. They are also rare in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, senior <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> officials praised the <LOCATION> Mitsui-Taiyo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kobe </LOCATION> deal as good business strategy. The national bankers' association also welcomed the merger. Although <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Taiyo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kobe </PERSON> were ranked seventh and eighth largest banks in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, each significantly larger than any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank, `` neither bank was really big enough to fulfill its ambitions on its own,'' said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Smithson </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Kleinwort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said it will look into the merger to see if it violates anti-trust laws, but the usually meek agency is not expected to block the deal. Next week, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials are expected to cite what they see as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s lax enforcement of anti-trust laws in talks on `` structural impediments'' to correcting <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s big surplus in trade with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. There have been fears that Japanese banks, with the enormous cash reserves pooled by thrifty Japanese savers, will dominate international markets just as Japanese car and electronics manufacturers have. In banking, largely through cheap pricing and high-volume business, Japanese banks already have made major inroads into <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> lending and in Eurobond issues. Because of their strong domestic market, where analysts estimate they make 90 percent of their profits, they can afford to take slim margins on their overseas business. But sheer size does n't necessarilymean profitability. <PERSON> Daichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kangyo </PERSON> is ranked first in the world in terms of assets, but only 77th in terms of return on equity, notes <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Waterhouse </PERSON>, an analyst at the securities house <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Capel </PERSON>. Some analysts say <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s banking is where its manufacturing was 20 years ago _ selling simple products cheap. But foreign analysts say Japanese banks are rapidly moving into more sophisticated products, starting to invent as well as copy, and that, combined with first-class skills, their size will be an enormous advantage. `` There could be implications for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> if Americans found themselves constrained by their own laws from reaching world size,'' said an American banker, speaking on condition of anonymity.
