<HEAD>Soybean Futures Rise On Freeze Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soybean futures prices jumped about 10 cents a bushel Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid fears that freezing temperatures could strike maturing crops in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> as early as next week. Corn and oat futures also finished higher while the wheat market was nearly unchanged. Some private meteorologists say the chance of an early freeze is greater than usual this year, based on weather patterns that caused <LOCATION> Midwestern </LOCATION> temperatures to drop to record lows earlier this month. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmerino </PERSON>, a senior agricultural meteorologist with <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, said his firm sees a 1-in-3 chance of a significant freeze in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> during September, compared with the normal odds of 1 in 15. But <PERSON> Palmerino </PERSON> said meteorologists predicting a freeze next week were likely using a forecasting model developed in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> whereas his firm uses a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> model that suggests rain followed by a warming trend in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> next week. Furthermore, he said, if a freeze were to occur in the Grain Belt next week, `` it would probably affect only a very small portion of the area,'' causing only marginal crop damage. At the close of trading, wheat was 1 -LCB- cents lower to 1 -LCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in September at $ 3.86 a bushel; corn was 2 -RCB- cents to 4 cents higher with September at $ 2.34 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 2 -LCB- cents to 4 cents higher with September at $ 1.35 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 10 -LCB- cents higher with September at $ 5.88 a bushel.
