<HEAD>Northeast Shortage May Shake Up Milk Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Milk supplies are drying up in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, which means consumers probably will have to pay up to 20 cents more per gallon by the end of the year, dairy experts said Thursday. `` It's good news for the dairy farmer because that means his price is going up,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stammer </PERSON>, senior vice president of economics and communications at <ORGANIZATION> Agri-Mark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a cooperative of about 2,200 dairy farmers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Milk is really short all the way from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> out to <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and clear down through the south,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Putnam </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, director of research at the Farm Credit Banks of <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>. Agriculture officials said they do n't anticipate a shortage of milk in stores. `` There is milk around, but the cost is going to be increased because they're going to have to go farther and farther west to get the milk,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Costa </PERSON>, assistant commissioner of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>. Dairy farmer <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, who runs a herd of about 170 on his <ORGANIZATION> Sunderland </ORGANIZATION> farm, said he hopes the shortage will translate into a better price. `` I'm optimistic,'' he said. A few years ago, the nation appeared awash in a milk surplus with the government installing price supports and giving away cheese in bulk amounts. However, there was no overflow in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, which produces only about 25 percent of its fluid milk needs. Now, the surplus is gone, partly because of a 1986 `` whole herd buyout,'' in which farmers sold their entire herds to the government for slaughter and promised to stay out of the dairy business for five years. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> imports much of its milk from <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which are in the same situation of low production at a time when consumption historically is high, <PERSON> Putnam </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, the number of dairy farms in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> has fallen from about 770 in 1984 to about 450. The buyout program is estimated to have reduced herds by 20 percent while rising land prices and competition from large <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> dairy farms also affected the state industry, officials said. `` The main reason that we're in the current situation is that the dairy farmers' prices pretty much constantly declined since 1983. This has driven a lot of farmers out of business,'' Stammer said. `` Right now, market prices are bidding up the price,'' said <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Plumb </PERSON>, chief of the order formulation division in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>'s dairy division. `` It's something that has n't been the case since the late 1970s in terms of dairy prices being market driven,'' he said. The shortage is being felt strongest in southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, Plumb said. In <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, Agriculture Commissioner <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> has issued permits to bring 100,000 pounds of milk this week into his state as schools order milk for returning children.
