<HEAD>Copper Futures Up Sharply On Renewed Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Copper futures prices surged in late trading Thursday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange on renewed supply jitters prompted by plans for a strike at a mine in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, the world's largest copper producer. On other markets, frost fears sent most grain and soybean futures higher; pork belly futures rose sharply while livestock futures were mixed; precious metals retreated; and energy futures advanced. Copper settled 2.95 cents to 3.35 cents higher with the contract for delivery in September at $ 1.3195 a pound. Copper miners at the <ORGANIZATION> Chilean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Copper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> mine were scheduled to walk out Friday, which would add a fourth major mine to those shut down worldwide by strikes, bankruptcy or terrorism. Copper futures prices generally have been rising over the past month in reaction to the industry's problems. The trend appeared to have changed Tuesday when prices plunged on signs of weakening unity among striking miners in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and some market analysts declared the bull market all but over. Those assumptions may have been premature, despite reports that leaders of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s mining union voted Wednesday to end their 18-day-old strike at midnight Thursday. A walkout at the <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> mine in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> would halt a production stream that produces 120,000 metric tons of refined copper a year, less than 2 percent of the 7-million-ton global output. The <LOCATION> Bougainville </LOCATION> mine in <LOCATION> Papua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION>, a 180,000-ton-a-year unit, has been closed due to terrorist attacks since late July; <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s Cananea copper mine, with an annual output of 95,000 tons, remains 