<TEXT>
 It's now possible to seal a deal with <ORGANIZATION> Tupperware </ORGANIZATION> on credit. The maker of the famous air-tight food and beverage containers now allows shoppers at <ORGANIZATION> Tupperware </ORGANIZATION> parties to make purchases using Visa or <ORGANIZATION> Mastercard </ORGANIZATION>, the company announced. The decision was made after testing credit card purchases earlier this year at several home and office `` parties,'' the only way to buy <ORGANIZATION> Tupperware </ORGANIZATION>, said company spokeswoman <PERSON> Lawrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitcher </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Tupperware </ORGANIZATION> has not been available in retail stores since 1951. Previously, guests at <ORGANIZATION> Tupperware </ORGANIZATION> parties could pay either by check or cash before delivery. The Kissimmee-based company also announced Wednesday that it now has more than 100,000 independent Tupperware dealers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said the credit card policy is part of recent modifications in the party system to meet changing lifestyles, including parties held in offices or in homes after work hours.
