<HEAD>Brazil Issues Bonds to Reduce Foreign Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government Thursday issued `` exit bonds'' to reduce interest payments on its massive foreign debt by $ 40 million a year. <PERSON> Marcelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceylao </PERSON>, a director at the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s equivalent of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, said $ 1.5 billion worth of the bonds were delivered simultaneously to financial markets in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> for distribution Friday The exit bonds will pay a fixed interest rate of 6 percent annually over a 25-year period. They substitute credit titles on old debt that were subject to the 9 percent Libor Rate on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> interbank market. A <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> communique released Thursday said it was the first time <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> issued new bonds to foreign markets since 1982. <PERSON> Ceylao </PERSON> told reporters that despite the Libor rate's higher yield, investors showed interest in swapping old debt for the certificates because the bonds are guaranteed. The certificates of custody on the bonds can be traded in a secondary market after 90 days, or converted into risk investments in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, tottering under a foreign debt of $ 110 billion, the Third World's largest, will pay $ 14.9 billion in interest payments this year, the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> estimates.
