<HEAD>Japanese Leader in Washington to Meet Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials were beginning trade and political talks Thursday with visiting Japanese Prime Minister <PERSON> Toshiki </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON>, who the day before rejected setting limits on his nation's exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The trip has been described as a get-acquainted visit for <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON>, 58, who took office on Aug. 9 after a money-for-sex scandal that toppled then-Prime Minister <PERSON> Sosuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Uno </PERSON> and contributed to a major defeat for his <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in elections to the upper house of parliament last month. A <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was interrupting his vacation in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, to meet with <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to `` stress the importance we attach to these talks and our desire to move forward,'' especially on trade issues. `` This is n't just a handshake and a photo. They have a lot of things to talk about,'' said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official, who spoke on condition he not be further identified. `` They are going to talk about bilateral trade and security issues, international questions, what has been going in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, and international debt.'' <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> began his <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trip Wednesday in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, where he told an impromptu news conference that controls on U.S.-Japan trade would `` stifle the dynamism'' of the two nations. He said the aim of his visit was `` to make rock-solid the relationship between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' Asked to comment on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s $ 55 billion annual trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> said: `` I plan to talk about this with the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. We will be continuing the dialogue.'' A senior <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official who briefed reporters in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> before the trip said <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> carried no major trade or diplomatic initiatives. <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> was meeting Thursday with Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, and on Friday with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and congressional leaders. He planned to travel Saturday to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, Monday to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, Wednesday to <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> and Friday to <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. His visit to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> falls a week before a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation, including Undersecretary of State for Economic and Agricultural Affairs <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON>, was to head to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> for talks designed in part to remove barriers to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, said the state department official.
