<HEAD>Aloha Airlines Buying New Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is buying four new <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737-300 jets and has options on four other jets to increase its fleet and replace older aircraft, the company announced Thursday. <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aloha </PERSON> president and chief executive officer, said the $ 250 million deal confirms the airline's confidence in sustained tourism growth in the 1990s. The first of the jets was expected to arrive in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> in 1992. The 737-300 model carries 139 passengers. Aloha currently has two 737-300s in its 13-plane fleet. <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said he expects <PERSON> Aloha </PERSON>'s fleet to continue growing at the rate of about one plane a year. He said the airline's oldest jets would be retired as necessary when the new planes arrive. In April 1988, an aging Aloha 737 blew open at 24,000 feet on a flight from <LOCATION> Hilo </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>. A flight attendant was swept to her death. The plane landed on <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> missing the front third of its passenger cabin roof.
