<HEAD>FCC Approves McCaw's Takeover Of Rival Cellular Phone Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday approved <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cellular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 5.5 billion hostile takeover of <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The commission denied assertions by <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION>, a New York-based cellular telephone, broadcasting and publishing concern, that <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON>'s bid for transfer of control of LIN's telephone and broadcasting licenses was not in the public interest and that <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> did n't have the money to make the deal. LIN also had argued that a hearing should be held to determine whether <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> held too much control of <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest non-wireline cellular telephone company, under laws limiting foreign investment in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> broadcasting companies; that the merger would be anticompetitive; that <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> would be too indebted; and that the merger would violate cable-television cross-ownership rules. In addition, <PERSON> LIN </PERSON> challenged the character of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> director who is president of the nation's largest cable TV operator, <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said it appeared that <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> would not exert direct control over the new company's television operations, but it conditioned its approval on McCaw providing an exact description of <PERSON> Malone </PERSON>'s position and duties and assurances he will comply with the cable-television cross-ownership restrictions. Overall, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said `` no good reason has been shown for the commission significantly to depart from its longstanding policy of strict neutrality and hence minimal intervention into the marketplace for corporate control.'' LIN operates seven network-affiliated television stations and has interests in cellular systems serving <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. It also owns a specialty publishing house that produces hard-cover tourist guides for hotel rooms. In May, LIN's board approved in principal spinning off all of the stock in a new subsidiary that would own its TV stations. It said it would operate its cellular operations along with the publishing business as a separate company. <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON>, Wash.-based <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> made a $ 110-per-share cash offer for all shares of <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION>'s stock in July, after first offering $ 120 a share. LIN management is seeking $ 127.50 a share for its 53.9 million shares, or nearly $ 6.9 billion. <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> already owns 5 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION> stock. <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> earlier this month extended its offer to Sept. 1. About 1.07 million LIN shares have been tendered, <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> said earlier this month. LIN said on July 31, its own deadline, that its board would pursue other options. <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> had asked the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> that, in order to speed the merger, LIN's licenses be transfered temporarily to a trustee representing its wholly owned subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> MMM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> But the commission said Thursday it could rule on the full application for transfer immediately. The commission said it generally does not consider debt or the level of debt as a relevant consideration in license transfers. As for assertions by LIN that <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> has n't lined up the financing necessary, the commission said <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> had `` well in excess of the amount needed to acquire LIN, with the balance more than adequate to operate the -LRB- LIN -RRB- television stations for three months.'' The commission said <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> had $ 1 billion in cash from the recent sale of stock to <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecom </ORGANIZATION>, the British phone company; $ 1.3 billion in revolving credit; $ 2 billion from a credit line from a bank syndicate headed by <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION>; and up to $ 2.5 billion from public or private equity or debt placements to be managed by <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The commission said <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecom </ORGANIZATION>'s 22 percent holdings in McCaw were within the 25 percent limits for foreign investors. The British government has a 48 percent ownership interest in <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, the parent of <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecom </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> also rejected LIN's request to look into possible anticompetitive rule violations by <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION>, the regional telephone company, which would be partnered with <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> through the merger, while competing with <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> in other areas. It also said no further action was warranted on LIN's assertions that <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> was not qualified to hold licenses because of his possible involvement in a cable franchise renewal proceeding in <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, that resulted in a multimillion-dollar verdict against <ORGANIZATION> TCI </ORGANIZATION> for antitrust violations. LIN's TV stations are: <ORGANIZATION> KXAS </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth-Dallas </LOCATION>; WISH, <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>; WOTV, <LOCATION> Battle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; WAVY, <ORGANIZATION> Hampton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roads </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> KXAN </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; WAND in central <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>; and WANE, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>.
