<HEAD>Dollar Opens Higher, Stock Prices Also Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar opened higher against the Japanese yen in early trading Friday, while share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> also gained. The dollar started trading at 144.95 yen, up 0.67 yen from Thursday's close. It finished at 145.03 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> overnight, up 0.80 yen from the previous day. <PERSON> Osamu </PERSON> <PERSON> Seto </PERSON>, a dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, said trust banks purchased dollars soon after the market opened following a dollar-buying trend in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. However, rumors on the market that a major life insurance company was waiting to sell a large amount of dollars exerted downward pressure on the dollar, <PERSON> Seto </PERSON> said. He said dealers were also waiting the announcement of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment rate in August, due for release in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> later Friday. But their long-term position adjustments would have more of an impact on the market than the jobless rate, he added. The 225-issue Nikkei Industrial Average rose 40.07 points, or 0.12 percent, to 34,471.27 shortly after the market opened.
