<HEAD>U.S. Appeals Court Upholds Ruling Against Regulations in Stock Disputes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court on Thursday upheld a lower court's decision to throw out controversial first-in-the-nation state regulations that would have made it easier for stock traders to sue brokers in financial disputes. The 1st U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> backed up <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodlock </PERSON>'s December 1988 ruling throwing out <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> regulations that prevent stockbrokers from requiring customers to seek arbitration in stock disputes. A coalition of brokers brought the case in September 1988 after <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> imposed the regulations, inspired by the 1987 stock market crash. The regulations would have required brokers to fully disclose the terms of their arbitration agreements and give customers the option of maintaining their right to sue in court. `` We can find no evidence of a clear congressional command to override the unambiguous pro-arbitration mandate of the -LRB- Federal Arbitration Act -RRB- in the securities field,'' the court opinion said. Other states interested in instituting requirements similar to the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> regulations were watching the case closely. Typically, the arbitration agreements state that in the event of a dispute, the customer and the broker would go into arbitration before a mutually acceptable party, such as the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, rather than take the case to court. Among those challenging the regulations were the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and 10 brokerage firms, including <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brokerage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Thousands of investors filed complaints alleging their urgent stock transactions were misplaced or mishandled during the stock market crash of October 1987 and many have said they prefer lawsuits to arbitration `` There's been a certain amount of suspicion that investors do n't get as good a result in arbitration as in court,'' said attorney <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rath </PERSON>, who represents the plaintiffs in the case `` But as far as I'm concerned that's unfounded.'' Telephone calls placed to <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON>'s office for comment Thursday evening were not answered.
